comment: An equivalence relation and specialization of coplanarLines (q.v.) that relates straight lines (see Line_Straight) that are parallel. (parallelLines LINE1 LINE2) is true if and only if (i) there is a Plane that spatiallySubsumes both LINE1 and LINE2 and (ii) LINE1 and LINE2 do not intersect (see spatiallyIntersects).
label: Parallel Lines
parallelLines

comment: (objectTopSide OBJECT BOTTOMSIDE) means that BOTTOMSIDE is the entire bottom surface part of OBJECT. See also TopAndBottomSidedObject and TopSide.

comment: (objectRetained SIT OBJ) means that in SIT, user rights to OBJ are retained (by some agent). See also agentRetaining and RetainingUserRights

objectRetained

comment: (linkCutSetInSystem SET SYS) means that the set SET of links in the ConnectedPathSystem SYS is a link-cut set in SYS, i.e., SET is a subset of (LinksFn SYS) such that cutting of all links in SET from SYS results in a disconnected path system. More strictly, to say that SET is a link-cut set in SYS, we mean that (LinksCut_SubSystemFn SYS SET) is not a ConnectedPathSystem. Note that when (linkCutSetInSystem SET SYS) holds, there could be some proper subset SUBSET of SET such that (linkCutSetInSystem SUBSET SYS) also holds. If you want a minimal link-cut set, without redundant links, use linkCutMinimalSetInSystem instead of linkCutSetInSystem.
label: Link Cut Set In System
linkCutSetInSystem

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function ProgramCopyFn. (programCopy X (ProgramCopyFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.

programCopy

comment: (nodeAddedToSOEGraph ADD NODE) means that in the event ADD, the node added to an SOE graph is NODE.

nodeAddedToSOEGraph

comment: (phoneNumberSuffix CONTACT_LOCATION NUM) means that NUM is the base phone number used at the ContactLocation CONTACT_LOCATION, ignoring the country code, area code, and exchange. When calling from one phone in certain exchanges to other telephones in the same exchange (or occasionally an associated exchange, as in some corporate offices) only the phoneNumberSuffix needs to be used to reach the other line.
label: Phone Number Suffix
phoneNumberSuffix

comment:
An InterAnimalRelationPredicate that is a specialization of both sexualPartners and positiveVestedInterest. (mate ANIMAL1 ANIMAL2) means that ANIMAL1 and ANIMAL2 are long-term companions. More general than spouse, mate can also be used to specify a person's "significant other", including one's boyfriend, girlfriend, or partner in a homosexual relationship.

An assumption in the UnitedStatesSocialLifeMt is that a person has at most one mate at any given time.
label: mate

comment:
An instance of FunctionalPredicate which relates a type of refined substance, REFINED-COLL, to the type of substance COLL of which REFINED-COLL is the refined form.

For example, (refinedMaterialOfType PetroleumProduct_Refined Oil) means that PetroleumProduct_Refined is the refined form of Oil.
label: Refined Material Of Type
refinedMaterialOfType

comment:
An AsymmetricBinaryPredicate and a specialization of parts. This predicate relates individuals to other individuals which are their proper parts (i.e., parts that are different from the whole).

(properParts WHOLE PART) means that:
(1) PART is a part of WHOLE (in the very broad sense in which parts is defined, meaning basically that a complete description of WHOLE would have to involve a description of PART), and
(2)PART is not identical to WHOLE itself.

There is a range of useful specializations of this predicate. For example, for individuals that are instances of Situation, see the more specific properSubSituations.
label: proper part
properParts

comment: (slopeRange VEHICLE ANGLE-RANGE) is the range of angles, downward to upward, at which VEHICLE is able to travel on an inclined off-road.
label: off-road slope range (degrees)
slopeRange-OffRoad

owl:incompatibleWith

(preferredSubjectRole EVENT-TYPE ROLE) means that ROLE best describes the role played by the referent of an active voice subject of a verb that denotes EVENT-TYPE.

preferredSubjectRole

comment: A binary predicate which relates instances of MoneyTransfer to instances of TenderObject, and indicates the financial instrument which is used in a particular transfer of money. (objectTendered TRANS OBJECT) means that the TenderObject OBJECT is used to transfer funds in the MoneyTransfer event TRANS. Note that OBJECT is distinct from the quantity of MonetaryValue (q.v.) transferred in TRANS (see the related predicate moneyTransferred), although of course OBJECT has some monetary value --- is `worth' a certain amount, generally calculated from the numbers printed or stamped or engraved on the TenderObject OBJECT --- which in turn is an instance of MonetaryValue.
label: tendered object
objectTendered

comment: (lexicalRootMtForLanguage MT LANG) means that MT is the most general LexicalMicrotheory which is specific to the NaturalLanguage, LANG.
label: Lexical Root Mt For Language
lexicalRootMtForLanguage

comment:
A AbsoluteLocationalPredicate and a specialization of partiallyLocatedAt_Spatial (q.v.) that holds between SpatialThings and Points. (locatedAtPoint_Spatial OBJECT POINT) means that OBJECT is located at POINT. This is a cross-dimensional locational predicate that can be used to indicate when the region occupied by some extended spatial object includes some point. See also #$incidentInSpaceRegion.

Note that locatedAtPoint_Spatial is irreflexive; in order to locate points in space use exactlyLocatedAt_Spatial.
label: point
locatedAtPoint-Spatial

scheduledIntervals

lengthAxis

comment: This predicate relates musical performers to audio conceptual works that they have recorded. (performerOfRecordedMusicalCW MUSICIAN MUSIC) means that MusicPerformanceAgent MUSICIAN is a performer on a recording of AudioConceptualWork MUSIC. Note that MUSICIAN need not have created (i.e., need not have originally authored) the work MUSIC -- the recording produced may be a "cover" of a work created by someone else.
label: Performer Of Recorded Musical CW
performerOfRecordedMusicalCW

comment: A MetaRelation predicate that is used to state how many things a given FixedArityRelation (q.v.) holds among or relates to one another. (relationalArity RELATION N) means that RELATION only holds among the members of N-item sequences or Lists (see relationHoldsAmong and relationExtension). If RELATION is any fixed-arity relation other than a function its relationalArity is the same as its ordinary arity (q.v.). But if RELATION is a FixedArityFunction its relationalArity is 1 greater than its arity. This reflects the fact that, qua relation, a function FUNC of arity N actually holds among N+1 things: FUNC's N arguments together with the corresponding value FUNC has for those arguments (see valueOfFunctionForArgs). For example, the function MotherFn has arity 1 while the corresponding predicate (see functionCorrespondingPredicate) biologicalMother has arity 2; but both of these relations have relationalArity 2.
label: Relational Arity
relationalArity

comment: This is a very general predicate inter-relating all things on the surface of the same planet. (onSamePlanetSurfaceAs THINGORPLACE1 THINGORPLACE2) means that the SpatialThing_Localized THINGORPLACE1 and the SpatialThing_Localized THINGORPLACE2 occur on or near the surface of the same planet. Thus the country denoted by France and any instance of the collection Bicycle in the CityOfPerthAustralia are so related.The relation denoted by onSamePlanetSurfaceAs holds between airplanes flying over the earth, people hopping on the earth, and people deep in a mine on the earth, but this relation does not hold between any of the aformentioned entities and a spacecraft deep in outer space, or the Moon, or Andromeda. Note that for thing T1 to be east of some other thing T2, or southwest of it, etc., it must be the case that T1 is on the same planet as T2.
label: On Same Planet Surface As
onSamePlanetSurfaceAs

comment: An assertion of the form (politicalOrgHasSupporter ORG AGENT) means that AGENT agrees with the principles and methods of ORG, though AGENT may not have a formal role within the organization's hierarhcy. This is a more general predicate than politicalPartyMembers, but a more specific predicate than both affiliatedWith and positiveVestedInterest. For instance, someone who attends rallies sponsored by or makes donations to a PoliticalOrganization would exemplify this relationship.
label: Political Org Has Supporter
politicalOrgHasSupporter

comment: (organismExposed EXPOSING ORG) means that ORG is an organism exposed to the BiochemicallyHarmfulSubstance that is the harmfulSubstanceExposedTo in EXPOSING.
label: Organism Exposed To Harmful Substance
organismExposedToHarmfulSubstance

comment: An instance of BinaryPredicate, used to identify a salient URL for a class of entities, which serves as a "root" for salient URLs for instances of that class. (salientURLRootForType TYPE PATHNAME) says that there are notable instances of TYPE that have salientURLs with the root URL of PATHNAME.

salientURLRootForType

comment: (ksSiblingKS KNOWLEDGE-SOURCE SIBLING) means that KNOWLEDGE-SOURCE inherits all ksImportationTemplate and ksTermString assertions from SIBLING. Essentially, KNOWLEDGE-SOURCE inherits all of SIBLING's terms and templates. This is different than '(genlMt KNOWLEDGE-SOURCE SIBLING); the knowledge source assimilation code utilizes information specific to a knowledge source's siblings but not its genlMt's. Note that the inheritance is not recursive; (ksSiblingKS KNOWLEDGE-SOURCE SIBLING) and (ksSiblingKS SIBLING OTHER-SIBLING) does not imply (ksSiblingKS KNOWLEDGE-SOURCE OTHER-SIBLING). (Maybe it should?)
A predicate corresponding to the function PopulationOfTypeFn. (populationOfType X (PopulationOfTypeFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Population Of Type
populationOfType

comment: A CycLReformulationRulePredicate that relates two CycL sentences. When asserted in a Microtheory MT, (reformulatorEquiv SENTENCE-1 SENTENCE-2) means that the CycLSentence SENTENCE-1 may be reformulated into the CycLSentence SENTENCE-2, or vice versa (based on meta-properties of this rule and what mode the reformulator is in), in any Microtheory SPEC-MT such that (genlMt SPEC-MT MT) holds. Free variables in SENTENCE-1 and SENTENCE-2 are shared, and may bind with CycL sentences which match the template. Note that (reformulatorEquiv SENTENCE-1 SENTENCE-2) does _not_ necessarily imply (equiv SENTENCE-1 SENTENCE-2), although this implication would hold if the reformulation is a TruthPreservingReformulation (q.v.).
label: Reformulator Equiv
reformulatorEquiv

comment: (peerComputers COMP1 COMP2) says that the Computers COMP1 and COMP2 are peers -- i.e., they are both peerWRTSuperPeer with respect to the same super-peer computer in an instance of SuperPeerNetwork. COMP1 and COMP2 can communicate with the super-peer, but not with each other.

peerComputers

comment: (preSituation EVENT SIT) means that the StaticSituation SIT holds just prior to the start of the Event EVENT, and SIT is directly related to EVENT in some salient way. The required `salience' of the two arguments to each other is difficult to formalize but usually intuitively clearcut. Commonly, SIT and EVENT share many of the same objects involved in various roles, and there is often a causal connection as well. For instance, if SIT is an instance of Configuration (q.v.), then SIT might be somehow `taken apart' by EVENT or might `trigger' EVENT.
label: Pre Situation
preSituation

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function ProductMadeOfFn. (productMadeOf X (ProductMadeOfFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.

productMadeOf

comment:
An instance of SpecificEntryFormatPredicate (q.v.). (openEntryFormatInArgs PRED N) means that, for any particular way of fixing the other arguments to PRED besides the Nth, there might be any number (including zero) of things such that, if taken as the Nth argument, PRED holds of those arguments. For example, openEntryFormatInArgs holds of biologicalMother with respect to its first argument-place, since a given female animal might have any number of offspring.

Unlike the other reified instances of SpecificEntryFormatPredicate, openEntryFormatInArgs actually places no restriction at all on what PRED might or might not hold of with respect to the specified argument-place. But one should not infer from this that openEntryFormatInArgs assertions are pointless; for they forestall duplication of effort by serving notice that the entry-format of a given argument-place has previously been considered and openEntryFormatInArgs was deemed appropriate.

openEntryFormatInArgs is the most commonly-encountered specific entry-format in the Cyc Knowledge Base. Contrast with singleEntryFormatInArgs.
label: Open Entry Format In Args
openEntryFormatInArgs

comment: (landmarksOfCity CITY THING) means that THING is generally considered to be a distinguishing 'landmark' of CITY in the context of the assertion, both by city residents and visitors.
label: Landmarks Of City
landmarksOfCity

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function LawsAboutTypeFn. (lawsAboutType X (LawsAboutTypeFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.

lawsAboutType

singular-Neuter

setOfGroupMembers

(Note that this predicate may relate a group to different sets at different times, though it not relate a group to more than one set at any given time.) This is the predicate corresponding to SetOfGroupMembersFn (q.v.).
A binary SpatialPredicate relates two-dimensional (or "flat" three-dimensional) spatial objects to their perimeters, which are ClosedLinearObjects. Also see the corresponding function PerimeterFn.

Instances of SituationSpecification are used to represent complex structural features that are common to the instances of a type of Situation. This is the most generic predicate for picking out subsituations based on their type. It plays a significant role in relation to instances of RoleSpecification where it is used to specify the type of subsituation which an instance of RoleSpecification represents.

liquidForm

comment: An assertion of the form (orgHasKeyIndividualMembers ORG PERSON) means that the Person PERSON is a member of the Organization ORG and that PERSON plays a significant role in guiding or implementing the actions of ORG. Important specializations of this predicate include companyHasCEO, seniorExecutives, primeMinister.

orgHasKeyIndividualMembers

comment: (parserTestTarget_Negative TEST TARGET) means that TARGET is an undesired parse for TEST. TEST will fail if TARGET is returned among the answers.

comment:
A TaxonomicSlot for SetOrCollections. (setOrCollectionUnion UNION SET-OF-CLASSES) means that UNION is the set-or-collection that is the union of all of the set-or-collections in SET-OF-CLASSES. More precisely, any thing THING is an elementOf UNION if and only if THING is an element of at least one element of SET-OF-CLASSES. Furthermore, we stipulate that (i) if each element of SET-OF-CLASSES is a set (see Set_Mathematical) then UNION is a set and (ii) if each element of SET-OF-CLASSES is a Collection then UNION is a collection. If the elements of SET-OF-CLASSES include both a set and a collection then UNION will either be a set or a collection, though in many cases we might not be able to determine which, and can only conclude that UNION is a SetOrCollection.

See the corresponding function SetOrCollectionUnionFn. Also see setOrCollectionUnion2 and setOrCollectionIntersection.
label: Set Or Collection Union
setOrCollectionUnion

comment:
A binary GeneralizedQuantifier. (most SOC1 SOC2) means that more than half of the elements of SOC1 are elements of SOC2.

Note that (most SOC1 SOC2) holds trivially when SOC1 is empty; for in that case, 100% of the elements of SOC1 are elements of SOC2.
label: Most (reflexive binary predicate)
most

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function MineFn. (mine X (MineFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Mine (predicate that is functional in its second argument)
mine

comment: A binary predicate which relates instances of NLWord_IBT to instances of SpeechPart. (possiblePOSOfWordIBT WORD-IBT POS) means that POS is one of the parts of speech that WORD-IBT could have. Note that there is not necessarily a unique part of speech for an NLWord_IBT, since it may instantiate more than one NLWordForm, corresponding to different parts of speech. For example, an instantiation of the character string "hit" may be either a Noun or a Verb.
label: Possible POS Of Word IBT
possiblePOSOfWordIBT

comment: managesRegion relates an instance of LegalGovernmentOrganization, typically a sub-organization of a RegulatoryAgency, to an instance of EcologicalRegion that the sub-organization manages.
label: Manages Region
managesRegion

comment: The predicate madeBy is used to indicate that a particular product was made by a particular company (or companies). (madeBy PROD COMORG) means that PROD, an instance of Product, was made by the CommercialOrganization COMORG. See also the predicate makesProductType.
label: Made By
madeBy

comment: (patchAppliedToComputer PATCH COMPUTER) means that the ComputerPatchProgram PATCH has been installed/run on COMPUTER and has thereby (presumably) removed some computer vulnerability from COMPUTER.
label: Patch Applied To Computer
patchAppliedToComputer

comment: (openingCeremonyFor CEREMONY FOCAL-OBJECT) means that CEREMONY is the instance of OpeningCeremony that "introduces" or "kicks off" the instance of Individual, FOCAL-OBJECT. Where FOCAL-OBJECT is an event, such as a conference or a sport season, CEREMONY will typically be the first sub-event (see firstSubEvents) or start shortly before FOCAL-OBJECT. Where FOCAL-OBJECT is an instance of Artifact, so that CEREMONY is an instance of DedicationCeremony, the temporal extent of FOCAL-OBJECT will typically start prior to CEREMONY.
label: Opening Ceremony For
openingCeremonyFor

comment: A binary predicate that relates PathSystems (q.v.) to the "points" in those systems. (pointInSystem POINT SYSTEM) means that POINT is either a "point" on a path in, or a "node" in SYSTEM. Each path system has at least one point. Note that virtually any type of Thing can in principle serve as a point in some path-system (which is why the first argument-place of pointInSystem is not constrained to, e.g., instances of Individual). The set of all _nodes_ in a given path-system is an important subset of the set of all _points_ in that system; see nodeInSystem for the difference between nodes and other (i.e. non-node) points. See also PointsInSystemFn.
label: Point In System
pointInSystem

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function ShoreOfLakeFn. (shoreOfLake X (ShoreOfLakeFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.
label: Shore Of Lake
shoreOfLake

richterMagnitude
comment: (momentMagnitudeOfEarthquake QUAKE NUMBER) means that NUMBER is the Richter magnitude of QUAKE. The Richter magnitude scale is used to indicate the energy released by earthquakes.

(possibleIntendedAttackTargets ATTACK OBJECT) means that OBJECT may have been an intended target of ATTACK -- that is, some relevant agent or source has reason to believe that (intendedAttackTargets ATTACK OBJECT) is true. (Note that the relevant notion of possibility here is an epistemic one.)

possibleIntendedAttackTargets

comment: (quantityOfChange TEMP-THING QUANT) holds just in case the temporal thing TEMP-THING has changed some quality in the quantity specified. this is a very general predicate since the type of change is not specified. When possible try to use a more informative predicate (c.f. changesQuantityInDirection).

quantityOfChange

programObjectRepresentsValue

comment: (potentialTargetForScriptedAttackType TARGET SCRIPTED-ATTACK-TYPE) holds just in case TARGET is a likely target for attacks of type SCRIPTED-ATTACK-TYPE. Depending on the attack type different conditions must hold for this to be true of some target. For instance, (potentialTargetForScriptedAttackType CHEMICAL-PLANT-01 AttackingAnInstallationByIntentionalPlaneCrash) holds, if the destruction of CHEMICAL-PLANT-01 is likely to cause panic or harm to the surrounding community and it is possible for the attack to occur. In order for this predicate to hold of some TARGET and attack type, it must be possible for there to exist an instance of the attack type, ATTACK in which (intendedAttackTargets ATTACK TARGET) holds. Furthermore, TARGET must be vulnerable to (in some sense) the type of attack indicated by SCRIPTED-ATTACK-TYPE -- Fort Knox will never be a potential target, in this sense, of AttackByBB-Gun even if some particular BB-gun attack targets it.
label: Potential Target For Scripted Attack Type
potentialTargetForScriptedAttackType

comment: A SpeechPartPredicate that relates a LexicalWord to a CharacterString. (plural_Feminine WORD STRING) means that STRING is the feminine plural form of WORD.
label: Plural-Feminine
plural-Feminine

comment: (objectSelected SEL OBJ) means that OBJ, an instance of SomethingExisting, is the object chosen in the event SEL, an instance of SelectingSomething.
label: thing selected
objectSelected

comment: (patient_Generic EVENT PATIENT) means that PATIENT plays a patient role in EVENT. PATIENT need not exist prior to EVENT (use objectActedOn for PATIENTS that pre-exist EVENT). Note that this is a very general predicate; in almost all representation cases you should be using a specPred of patient_GenericDirect. Example: in a GivingSomething event where Sally gives Fred a book, the book is playing a patient_GenericDirect role (namely objectOfPossessionTransfer), Sally is playing a doneBy role (namely fromPossessor and therefore deliberateActors) and Fred is playing a patient_GenericIndirect role (namely toPossessor).
label: undergoer of the action
patient-Generic

comment: A binary predicate that relates an agent to a structured activity (see DevisedStructuredActivity) s/he practices or engages in. (practicesStructuredActivity AGENT ACTIVITY) means that AGENT practices ACTIVITY. Specializations of this predicate include onDietProgram.
label: Practices Structured Activity
practicesStructuredActivity

QRS Duration
qRSDuration
comment: The QRS complex is a structure of waves depicted in an ECG graph that corresponds to the depolarization of the ventricles.  The QRS duration is the duration of the QRS complex from start to finish.  "QRS" refers to Q-wave, R-wave, and S-wave -- waves recorded on an ECG graph -- though only at least one of the three waves are required for it to be a QRS complex.

(ngaUniqueNameIdentifier NAME IDNUM) states that the NationalGeospatialIntelligenceAgency_US uses the Integer, IDNUM, as the unique identifier for the USBGNPlaceName, NAME. IDNUM may be positive or negative. Currently, only names given to geographic features outside the UnitedStatesOfAmerica and its territories are assigned a number as a ngaUniqueNameIdentifier.
label: Nga Unique Name Identifier
ngaUniqueNameIdentifier

lFEventName3

comment: (pointClosedSubSystems SYS SUBSYS) means that the path system SUBSYS is a subsystem of the path system SYS (i.e., (subPathSystems SYS SUBSYS) holds) and SUBSYS 'preserves' all points in SYS that are on links in SUBSYS, i.e., if LINK is a link in SUBSYS (and hence is a link in SYS) and X is a point in SYS and is on LINK, then X must be a point in SUBSYS.
label: Point Closed Sub Systems
pointClosedSubSystems

comment: A symmetric binary predicate that relates organisms (see Organism_Whole). (relatives ORGANISM1 ORGANISM2) means that ORGANISM1 is a relative of ORGANISM2. In the case of organisms other than humans, a relatives relationship is established only via reproduction (sexual or asexual); see the specialization biologicalRelatives. In the case of humans, however, a relatives relationship can be established also via certain social arrangements, such as Adoption, marriage, or fostering.
label: relative
relatives

comment: (militaryAttache_OrganizationalRole ORG PERSON) means that PERSON who has been 'attached' to the non-military Organization ORG. Ordinarily, PERSON is a member of the armed forces of the GeopoliticalEntity to whose government ORG is subordinated. Responsibilities for military attaches vary with the organization to which they are subordinated, but may include providing security personal protection for members of the organization's staff, and various liason activities.
label: military attache
militaryAttache-OrganizationalRole

comment: (relationExists PRED COL) means that for some instance INST of COL, (PRED INST) holds. Thus (relationExists PRED COL) is equivalent to the more complex form: (thereExists ?INST (isa ?INST COL) (PRED ?INST)). A ground atomic formula (or "GAF") built upon relationExists is in effect shorthand (i.e. a "macro") for an equivalent assertion with the more complex quantified form. See the shared #$NoteAboutUseOfRuleMacroPredicates.
label: Relation Exists
relationExists

comment: (negativeInterest-Prop AGT PROP) means that AGT has a con-attitude towards PROP -- i.e., AGT has a negative interest in PROP being or becoming true. negativeInterest_Prop is a generalization of more specific con-attitude predicates such as embarrassed, fears, regrets. In contrast with desires and goals, negativeInterest_Prop is not strictly future-directed. An agent may have a negative interest in a proposition which already holds. Indeed, this is always the case with such backward-looking emotional attitudes such as embarrassed and regrets. It captures the sense in which these emotions involve a wishing that something that is the case not be so.
label: Negative Interest Prop
negativeInterest-Prop
Publication Time Of MTAssertions
publicationTimeOfMTAssertions
comment:
(publicationTimeOfMTAssertions MICROTHEORY TIME-INTERVAL) means that the assertions in the Microtheory MICROTHEORY were published (or at least publically made) during the TimeInterval TIME-INTERVAL. For example, the 'publication time' of the CIAWorldFactbook1997Mt is the year 1997.

Note that the time interval in question is not necessarily that referenced in assertions within MICROTHEORY; for example, the CIAWorldFactbook1997Mt contains assertions about the 1996 gross domestic product of various countries.

Nor should it be interpreted as the time-interval at which the assertions within MICROTHEORY are true; for an expression of that idea, see mtTime (and MtTimeFn).

Nor is it the date on which assertions in MICROTHEORY were entered in Cyc. Again, the CIAWorldFactbook1997Mt is a good example, since it was created in 1998. Generally, when the source of the assertions in a microtheory is a publication, the 'publication time' will be the date of publication. (Specifically, the date of first publication, in the case of unrevised subsequent editions. However, if the material in the source is made publically available prior to the formal publication date, the 'publication time' will be the earlier date.) Note that it will only make sense to assign an 'publication time' to a microtheory when it represents a set of propositions that were all asserted (or hypothesized, or...etc.) by some specific source or agent -- many microtheories do not fall into this category.

comment:
A MetaKnowledgePredicate that is used to express that a pragmatic precondition on a given rule is satisfied. The predicate takes as arguments a list of CycL variables and an asserted rule (see CycLRuleAssertion) in which those variables occur "free". At the EL ("epistemological level"), meetsPragmaticRequirement sentences are not asserted as GAFs, but appear instead as the consequents of system-generated implies rules. For a given sequence of values for the respective variables VAR1, ..., VARn, (meetsPragmaticRequirement (TheList VAR1 ... VARn) RULE) means that some pragmatic precondition placed on RULE's being used by the Cyc inference engine (see pragmaticRequirement) is satisfied with respect to those values.

Let's make this more precise and explicit. A pragmatic precondition for a rule is written like so: 

   (pragmaticRequirement CONDITION RULE)

and gets canonicalized into a rule involving meetsPragmaticRequirement like so: 

   (implies
     CONDITION
    (meetsPragmaticRequirement (TheList VAR1 ... VARn) RULE)),

where VAR1, ..., VARn are all and only the variables that occur free in RULE and thus include all (and possibly only) the variables that occur free in CONDITION (i.e. as RULE and CONDITION explicitly appear in the KB browser, without consideration of their having "implicit" initial universal quantifiers).

The above meetsPragmaticRequirement rule is used in inference similarly to an abnormal rule. If CONDITION is not known to hold for a given sequence of values <VAL1, ..., VALn> for its variables <VAR1, ..., VARn>, then those values do not "meet the pragmatic requirement" for RULE; and hence inference will not proceed using <VAL1, ..., VALn> with RULE.

The effect of the foregoing is that any asserted rule RULE is implicitly treated by the Cyc inference engine as if it had the form 

 (implies
  (meetsPragmaticRequirement (TheList VAR1 ... VARn) RULE)
   RULE)

(with VAR1, ..., VARn as described above).

This convention allows the logical content of a rule to be expressed independently of any pragmatic preconditions for its being used in inference. If a rule has multiple pragmatic requirements, it must meet all of them to be used in inference.

Also see abnormal, which is syntactically similar and has a related interpretation.
label: Meets Pragmatic Requirement
meetsPragmaticRequirement

A trivial source, in contrast, is the mechanism used to assert ASSERTION (such as the work of a particular cyclist -- see assertionAssertBy).

For example, the assertion '(literacyRateForGroupInRegion Estonia Person (Percent 100))' was asserted into the KB by Kathy Panton, and she got this information from the CIA 1997 World Factbook. sourceOfAssertion_NonTrivial is defined to indicate that the CIA 1997 World Factbook, not Kathy, is the non-trivial source.

comment: (maximalConnectedSubSystems SYS SUB) means that SUB is a maximal connected subsystem of SYS, i.e., that SUB is an entire connected piece of SYS without other disconnected pieces of SYS. That is to say, (i) SUB is a connected path system (see the collection ConnectedPathSystem), and consequently must have at least one node, say NODE, in it, (ii) SUB is a subsystem of SYS, and (iii) for every connected subsystem SUB1 of SYS containing NODE, SUB1 is a subsystem of SUB. Thus a maximal connected subsystem SUB of a path system SYS must satisfy the conditions that (a) for each point X in SUB and each point Y in SYS that is not in SUB, X and Y are not connected in SYS, (b) for any nodes X and Y in SUB, for any link LINK in SYS between X and Y, LINK must also be in SUB, and (c) for each point X in SYS, if X is on a link in SYS which is also a link in SUB, then X must also be in SUB. It follows that if SUB is a maximal connected subsystem of SYS, SUB must be a link-closed subsystem as well as a point-closed subsystem of SYS. Another consequence is that if SUB is a maximal connected subsystem of SYS, and if X is a point in SUB and is on a loop in SYS, then the loop must also be in SUB.
label: Maximal Connected Sub Systems
maximalConnectedSubSystems

comment:
This predicate relates an IntegratingASetOfKnowledgeSources to a list of length at least two of sets of ObjectDefiningSchemas, where each set in the list is set of input schemas for the integration all of the same type. (See schemaIntegrationTypeForInputODSSet). The list is ordered by the respective type corresponding to each set, using SetOfCollectionSpecializationListsFn. That is, (schemaIntegrationInputODSSetSubsumptionList INTEGRATION INPUT-ODS-SET-LIST) is calculated as follows:

1. Find the ODS-TYPE-SET for INTEGRATION using schemaIntegrationObjectFieldTypeSet;

2. Apply SetOfCollectionSpecializationListsFn to ODS-TYPE-SET to obtain TYPE-SPECIALIZATION-LIST-SET;

3. Take an element, TYPE-SPECIALIZATION-LIST, of TYPE-SPECIALIZATION-LIST-SET of length at least two (to avoid pathological and uninteresting cases);

4. Replace each member, TYPE, of TYPE-SPECIALIZATION-LIST with its corresponding INPUT-ODS-SET, found by looking up on schemaIntegrationTypeForInputODSSet.

This predicate is used in further analysis of the input schemas to determine the correct set of logical fields and meaning sentences for their corresponding target schemas, and to properly record schema inheritence in the target model (see odsExtendsODS)..
label: Schema Integration Input ODS Set Subsumption List
schemaIntegrationInputODSSetSubsumptionList

comment: The predicate roleMapSpecification_Disjoint is used to represent that, in the instances of a given type of Situation and in those instances subsituations, that the actors in particular roles must be numerically different individuals. An assertion of the form (roleMapSpecification_Disjoint SIT-YPE RM-SPEC) connects the RoleMappingSpecification to the type of Situation to which it applies, SIT-TYPE. RM-SPEC will be associated with several instances of RoleSpecification, each of these will pick out a role either in the instances of SIT-TYPE themselves or in their subsituations. Specifically, given the assertions (subSpecification_Subject RM-SPEC ROLE-SPEC1) and (subSpecification_Object RM-SPEC ROLE-SPEC2), then any individual who plays the role picked out by ROLE-SPEC1 in an instance of SIT-TYPE cannot also play the role picked out by ROLE-SPEC2 in the same instance of SIT-TYPE. It is possible for RM-SPEC to be connected to many instances of RoleSpecification. Although the label 'disjoint' on this predicate indicates a symmetric relationship, this predicate is associated with the predicates subSpecification_Subject and subSpecification_Object in order to efficiently represent multiple disjoint roles through a single instance of RoleMappingSpecification. Thus, if it is known that one set of roles is disjoint with another set of roles and each set shares actors among its roles, then one set can be picked out with the 'subject' predicate and the other can be picked out with the 'object' predicate without entailing any unwanted disjointness claims.
label: Role Map Specification Disjoint
roleMapSpecification-Disjoint

A specialization of equals and a CycLReformulatorConstant that relates pairs of CycLClosedDenotationalTerms. rewriteOf is, in a sense, a "directional" version of equals. (rewriteOf FAVORED-TERM DISFAVORED-TERM) means that (1) FAVORED-TERM and DISFAVORED-TERM denote the same thing, and (2) FAVORED-TERM is deemed worthy of being privileged over DISFAVORED-TERM in the following senses: assertions made on DISFAVORED-TERM will be propagated to FAVORED-TERM, and whenever possible attempts to reason about DISFAVORED-TERM will be transformed into attempts to reason about FAVORED-TERM. The propagated assertions will differ from the original assertions only in that the propagated assertions will be the result of substituting FAVORED-TERM for DISFAVORED-TERM wherever DISFAVORED-TERM occurs in the original assertions. Note that substitution does not happen in the opposite direction. That is, assertions containing FAVORED-TERM will not propagate to DISFAVORED-TERM.

One common use of rewriteOf is that in which FAVORED-TERM is a syntactically simpler term than DISFAVORED-TERM. For example, FAVORED-TERM may contain fewer nested terms that denote Function_Denotationals than does DISFAVORED-TERM. (rewriteOf UnitedStatesNavy (NavyFn UnitedStatesOfAmerica)) is a good example of this common sort of use.

Note that rewriteOf expresses a strictly conventional notion of "directional" equality. Pragmatic considerations, not ontology, will dictate which term is chosen to occur as the privileged (left-hand side) term in a rewriteOf assertion. Thus, in the example the fact that simpler terms are generally easier to use (remember, manipulate, etc.) dictates that UnitedStatesNavy should be a rewrite of (NavyFn UnitedStatesOfAmerica), and not vice versa.
label: Rewrite Of
rewriteOf

comment:
(latitude THING ANGULAR-DISTANCE) means that the SpatialThing THING is located at the north latitude ANGULAR-DISTANCE, in the sense that either the whole of THING lies at this latitude or THING has a proper part which lies at this latitude. Thus if THING is, for instance, a large geographical region, there can be more than one true assertion of the form (latitude THING X). Some examples of assertions about latitude are:

(latitude EarthsEquator (Degree_UnitOfAngularMeasure 0)),
(latitude AxialNorthPoleOfEarth (Degree_UnitOfAngularMeasure 90)), and
(latitude AntarcticCircle (Degree_UnitOfAngularMeasure -66.5)).

As the last example indicates, latitudes of things in the southern hemisphere are expressed using negative real numbers.
label: Latitude (interval-based quantity measure)

comment:
A specialization of sizeParameterOfObject. (polarRadiusOfSpheroid SPHEROID DISTANCE) means that DISTANCE is one-half the length of SPHEROID's polar axis.

Whenever two symmetricAxes (q.v.) of a Spheroid that is not a perfect Sphere have the same length, they are both equatorial axes of the spheroid (cf. equatorialRadiusOfSpheroid). All of the equatorial axes of such a spheroid lie in a single plane; and the (unique) symmetric-axis of the spheroid that is perpendicular with its equatorial axes is known as its polar axis.

If a spheroid's equatorial radius is greater than its polar radius, it is an OblateSpheroid; if its polar radius is greater than its equatorial radius, it is a ProlateSpheroid. The greater radius (whichever it might be) measures the spheroid's semi-major axis (see spheroidSemimajorAxisLength). A Sphere's polar and equatorial radii are both equal to its ordinary radius.

Note that, since an axis is a Line_Straight, it strictly speaking has infinite length. So when we say that a given axis AXIS of a spheroid SPHEROID has the length DISTANCE, it is really shorthand for saying that the line-segment part of AXIS whose endpoints are where AXIS intersects SPHEROID has length DISTANCE.
label: Polar Radius Of Spheroid
polarRadiusOfSpheroid

A NumericComparisonPredicate that is a generalization of the mathematical less-than ( < ) relation to ScalarIntervals (q.v.) of all sorts, including quantitative intervals as well as point values (see ScalarPointValue). (lessThan VALUE1 VALUE2) means that VALUE1 is less than VALUE2 with respect to some scale that they are both on. More precisely, there is some TotallyOrderedScalarIntervalType SCALE that both VALUE1 and VALUE2 are instances of and either (i) SCALE is a specialization of NumericInterval (e.g. RealNumber) and the maximum (see maxQuantValue) of VALUE1 is less than the minimum (see minQuantValue) of VALUE2 or (ii) (followingValueOnScale VALUE1 VALUE2 SCALE) holds. Note that lessThan is an ELRelation (q.v.), and the above sentence would actually canonicalize to (greaterThan VALUE2 VALUE1).
label: lessThan

The predicate mtImageDepicts is used to determine things represented in images, on the basis of the information content of the image. For this purpose, the content of an image is represented as an abstract, propositional thing--an element of ImageMicrotheory (which is a subset of PropositionalInformationThing (q.v.)). (mtImageDepicts IMT OBJ) means that the image(s) which have the information content IMT depict the object OBJ. Those images may be still or moving images. IMT is an element of ImageMicrotheory. OBJ is an element of SpatialThing, which includes both tangible objects and physical events. One usage of mtImageDepicts is for the description and representation of particular images; e.g., an image with the content `Roy Rogers is riding Trigger' depicts Roy Rogers and depicts Trigger. Another usage of mtImageDepicts is in inference rules about the content of images. For example, using a series of common sense inferences, we conclude that an image with the content `a cowboy [is] on his horse' probably also depicts some instance of OutdoorLocation.
label: Mt Image Depicts

comment: (motionPathway_Exact MOVE PATH) indicates that the trajectory or trajectories travelled by one or more objects during a movement event is the spatial path PATH. If MOVE is an instance of Translation_MultiTrajectory, (motionPathway_Exact MOVE PATH) means that the instance PATH of Path_Spatial is the entire instance of Trajectory along which at least one of the objects moving in MOVE travels. In this case, more than one motionPathway_Complete may exist. (Note that the instance of Traversal determined by the trajectory-Complete need not occupy the whole length of PATH.) To explain this predicate somewhat differently, any motionPathway_Complete of an instance of Movement_TranslationEvent connects the starting and stopping points (the fromLocation and toLocation) of the whole trajectory of at least one object in the movement event (See also pathConnects). ARGN-PRIME ...) hold, then if (argIsa PRED N SpatialThing) and (argIsa PRED N TemporallyExistingThing) then (spatiallyIntersects ARGN ARGN-PRIME) holds (i.e. (not (spatiallyDisjoint ARGN ARGN-PRIME)) holds) and (temporallyIntersects ARGN ARGN-PRIME) holds (i.e. (not (temporallyDisjoint ARGN ARGN-PRIME)) holds).

comment: (loopInSystem LOOP SYS) means that LOOP is a 'loop' in SYS, which is like a link in SYS except that it has exactly one node on it as if it is a link whose two end nodes are the same. Each loop in SYS is also a cycle in SYS, see cycleInSystem. The differences between a loop and a (non-loop) cycle in SYS include that (i) there is exactly one point in SYS on a loop (which must be a node in SYS), but there may in general be any finite number of nodes (and even as many points as there are real numbers) on some (non-loop) cycle in SYS, and that (ii) The unique node in SYS on a loop may or may not be an end point of a link in SYS, but each node on a (non-loop) cycle in SYS must be an end point of at least two links in SYS. These imply that there can be at most one 'intersection point' on a loop in SYS but there can be any finite number of 'intersection points' on a (non-loop) cycle in SYS. See pointOnCycle and junctionInSystem. Note that under current treatment of loops in a path system, if one would like to talk about a 'loop' in a path system a 'part' of which is a path in the system, then he/she should make it a cycle rather than a loop in the system because according to what we said above, no 'part' of a loop in the system can be presented as a path in the system. Note also that in some cases (such as talking about relations between different PathSystems), using (LoopsInSystemFn SYS) to denote the set of all loops in SYS is more convenient than using the predicate loopInSystem.
label: Loop In System
loopInSystem

Not Abducible For Arg

comment: An assertion of the form (notAbducibleForArg PRED N) represents a restriction on hypothesis formation relative to abductive inferences. Specifically, Cyc cannot hypothesize values for the Nth argument position in an assertion whose zeroth argument is PRED. Abductive inferences often seek to explain an assertion or set of assertions by hypothesizing the truth of other assertions. However, we wish to restrict the kinds of assertions which Cyc will hypothesize such that Cyc does not hypothesize new theoretical or conceptual knowledge. The predicate notAbducibleForArg is used to restrict the values which Cyc could hypothesize for an assertion involving PRED. For example, consider the assertion (notAbducibleForArg makesProductType 2). The assertion (makesProductType ORG TYPE) states that the instance of Organization ORG produces instances of ProductType TYPE. While we don't want to hypothesize that a known organization makes novel types of products, we would be more willing to accept that an unknown organization makes a particular type of product. More specifically, while we wouldn't want to hypothesize (makesProductType DunkinDonuts_Corporation Handgun), it would be useful to hypothesize the existence of organizations that produce the kinds of products that known organizations also produce. Thus, (makesProductType (The Organization) Doughnut) might be a useful hypothesis within an abductive inference.

comment: This is a generic "needs" predicate that generalizes over a fairly diverse range of predicates having to do with an agent's needing something in order to attain some goal or other. In most cases, one of these more specialized predicates should be used instead of needs_Generic itself. The sense of "needs" intended here includes everything from moderate practical convenience to matters of life and death, so as to cover all sorts of situations in which one might say that "So-and-so _needs_ such-and-such", where this need is currently unfulfilled (e.g. the agent So-and-so does not, at least yet, have the thing such-and-such). (needs_Generic AGENT THING) means that AGENT has a need with respect to THING, where AGENT's satisfying that need is -- given AGENT's current circumstances -- practically necessary for AGENT's achieving or furthering some goal (see goals) that s/he has. By "practically necessary" we mean that, if this need of AGENT's goes unsatisfied, then AGENT is unlikely to achieve or further that goal, at least not without being significantly delayed or otherwise inconvenienced. For example, suppose I am in the habit of driving several miles to work each morning in my (only) car. Given those circumstances, I might well say that I need my car to get to work tomorrow. Now, if I were unexpectedly to be denied access to my car tomorrow (e.g. if it were stolen overnight), I could probably still make it to work (by taking a bus, walking, or whatever), but getting there would involve extra hassling and take longer than usual. Of course, it's _conceivable_ that a Good Samaritan might happen by and kindly offer to drive me directly to work; but the likelihood of something like that occurring is poor. Thus, all things considered, the claim that -- in a practical, everyday sense of "need" -- I need my car to get to work tomorrow seems legitimate. Second example: Suppose I've just ingested a fatal dose of poison X, whose only (known or unknown) antedote is substance Y. I need a dose of antedote Y (to further my goal of continuing to live); if I don't get it I'll die -- period. It is this broad sense of the word "need" -- ranging from moderate practical convenience to requirements for something's continued existence-- that the various specializations of needs_Generic (each with respect to its own particular domain of application) are intended to represent. See also needsFor and satisfiesNeed.
label: Needs-Generic
needs-Generic

comment: This predicate relates potential service recipients to service providers that are bound to provide services of some type to that agent. The first argument place should be the potential recipient of service and the second argument place should contain the potential service provider. The relationship holds while the agreement to provide the service is in place, not just while the service is being provided. This agreement need not be a formal agreement but it should involve the service provider in a task for which he, she, it or the service provider's controller is paid, although not necessarily by the service recipient. Hence, mother is not a specpred (specs) of this predicate but the relationship between a client and social worker or between parishioner and priest might be even if the client or parishioner does not pay for the service. If a company, Company001, puts a lawyer, Lawyer001, on retainer, then it is true that (receivesServicesFrom Company001 Lawyer001) even before the lawyer has provided any services. Usually it is preferable to use one of the specializations of this predicate. See, for instance, accountants, attorneys or hasWorkers. receivesServicesFrom is more general than hasWorkers as it can describe the relationship between a person and her dentist or priest and the relationship between an organization that may occassionally receive a service from an agent, e.g. a subcontractor. If a business, Business001 has a certain accountancy firm, AccountantsRUs001, perform occasional bookkeeping work, it is not true throughout the year that (hasWorkers BusinessOO1 AccountsRUs001) but it may be true throughout the year that (receivesServicesFrom Business001 AccountantsRUs001).
label: recipient of services
receivesServicesFrom

comment: An AgentiveRole and a specialization of performedBy. (perpetrator ACTION PERP) means that the SocialBeing PERP is a perpetrator of the arguably criminal ACTION. More precisely: PERP performs ACTION, where ACTION is likely to be considered criminal by some observers (or at least would be so considered in some contexts). Note that the first argument of perpetrator is not constrained (see argIsa) to CriminalActs, since an act that counts as criminal in one context might not count as criminal in another context, and yet we might still want to talk about the "perpetrator" of that act in the latter context.
label: perpetrator

comment:
A NumericComparisonPredicate and a specialization of numericallyEquals, minQuantValue, and maxQuantValue (qq.v.). pointQuantValue is essentially the relation numericallyEquals restricted to scalar point-values, with the additional proviso that its first argument must be given using a reifiable CycL term. Thus a sentence of the form

(pointQuantValue REIFIABLE-TERM OTHER-TERM)

is true if and only if REIFIABLE-TERM is a CycLReifiableDenotationalTerm (q.v.), and REIFIABLE-TERM and OTHER-TERM denote the same ScalarPointValue (q.v.).

This predicate is primarily used to state the equivalence of a reified scalar-denoting term (e.g. 'Zero', 'AvogadrosNumber', 'SpeedOfLight') with an appropriate unreifiable term. For example, both of the following sentences hold: 

  (pointQuantValue Zero 0)


  (pointQuantValue
    SpeedOfLight

comment:
A MetaPredicate for stating that two predicates are logical "contraries" of one another. (negationPreds PRED1 PRED2) means that if PRED1 holds among a given sequence of things, then PRED2 does not hold among that sequence (and vice versa). Thus it is equivalent to 
  (not (and (PRED1 . ARGS) (PRED2 . ARGS))) .
For example, (negationPreds owns rents) holds, as one cannot both own and rent a given thing at the same time.

Note that the argument types of PRED1 and PRED2 need not be the same, they merely must not be disjoint. Note also that PRED1 and PRED2 are constrained (see e.g. interArgIsa) either to both having the same fixed-arity (see FixedArityRelation) or to both having variable-arity (see VariableArityRelations).

See also genlPreds and negationInverse.
label: mutually-negating predicate
negationPreds

comment: A predicate used for probability statements. (lessLikelyThan_Derived PROPOSITION1 PROPOSITION2) means that, in the applicable Microtheory, the <em>a posteriori</em> derivedProbability that PROPOSITION1 is true is less than the <em>a posteriori</em> derivedProbability that PROPOSITION2 is true, taking into account other evidence and the truth or falsehood of other assertions. This predicate does not say what the probabilities actually are numerically; it is just an ordering (or rather partial ordering) relation between the two propositions. In most microtheories, generally, this lessLikelyThan_Derived means that the probability that PROPOSITION1 is true is less than the probability that PROPOSITION2 is true, given the probabilities of other CycLAssertions in the Microtheory and the domainAssumptions accessible in the Microtheory. Contrast this with atLeastAsLikelyAs (which makes no claim of dependence on or independence from other assertions) and with lessLikelyThan_Prior (which does not take into account any dependence on other assertions). This definition makes no presumption as to determinism versus nondeterminism, nor as to whether probability is only in the mind of some beholder. The definition allows for any of several different systems of deriving the probability of one assertion from the probabilities of, or conditional probabilities relating, other assertions.
label: Less Likely Than Derived
lessLikelyThan-Derived

comment: A RelativeLocationalPredicate (q.v.) and an EquivalenceRelation. This is indeed the most general of all SpatialPredicates (q.v.), in that it is by design a generalization (via either genlPreds or genlPredsWRTArgs) of every spatial predicate. (spatiallyRelated THING1 THING2) means that THING1 and THING2 are somehow spatially related to each other. This implies that the two things are embedded within the same surrounding space, but does not specify any more particular spatial relation between them. Thus, any two spatial objects located in the empirically-observable universe (see SpatialThing_Localized) are spatiallyRelated to each other. Conversely, two spatial things that are embedded in different spaces (e.g. an object in the physical universe and a geometric figure in an abstract space defined in the context of a geometry problem) are not spatially related.
label: Spatially Related

comment:
A very general signification or representation predicate. (signifies SIGNIFIER SIGNIFIED) means that the Thing SIGNIFIED is signified by the Individual SIGNIFIER. That is, SIGNIFIER somehow represents, refers to, denotes, or depicts SIGNIFIED. As an instance of Thing, SIGNIFIED can be anything. SIGNIFIER can be almost anything, although it is most often a word, phrase, description, string, image or symbol. Note that this predicate does not state to whom SIGNIFIER represents SIGNIFIED; that is some assumed 'interpreter' or 'community of interpreters' in the given context, and it is left implicit by this binary predicate. In order to mention explicitly the interpreter or agent to whom SIGNIFIER means SIGNIFIED, use the ternary predicate signifiesTo.

Often there is a convention (intersubjective understanding and agreement) by which one thing represents another, such as the word 'Dogs' referring (in English) to dogs, or the abstract tetrahedron referring to the element Fire in Alchemy. A pile of three rocks on a path can signify 'danger ahead' and the number thirteen can signify bad luck (such signification is sometimes called "symbolic".) But there need be no specific convention; deer tracks in the sand can signify the deer (such signification is sometimes called "indexical"), and a picture or photograph may signify whatever it is a picture of (such signification is sometimes called "iconic"), in both cases without any prior convention or agreement. An important specialization of this predicate is denotes, which restricts SIGNIFIER to instances of CycLExpression, and the relationship between SIGNIFIER and SIGNIFIED to that of denoting (i.e. directly referring to).

occursDuring is a binary predicate relating an event to a time interval in which it occurs. (occursDuring EVENT TIMEINTERVAL) means that the event EVENT occurs entirely within the time interval TIMEINTERVAL. Thus, (occursDuring EVENT TIMEINTERVAL) implies that (temporallySubsumes TIMEINTERVAL EVENT). For example, if ASSN is the assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr., then (occursDuring ASSN (YearFn 1968)). See also dateOfEvent.
label: Occurs During
occursDuring

comment: (spatiallyIntrinsicArg PRED N) means that the Predicate PRED expresses a property that is "spatially intrinsic" for its argument position N. In other words, if a sentence S using PRED is true for some object OBJ (in the Nth argument position), every sentence is true in which a term denoting any spatial part (via physicalPortions) of OBJ is substituted for OBJ in S. For example, since (spatiallyIntrinsicArg temperatureOfObject 1) is true, if it is true that (temperatureOfObject Coffee007 (DegreeCelsius 90)), it is true that any spatial part of "Coffee007" will also have that temperature. An example of a property that is not spatially intrinsic is massOfObject; there are parts of any object that have less mass than the entire object. Another example of a relation that is not spatially intrinsic, but might at first seem to be, is constituents. In (constituents ChocolateMilk37 Milk36), it is not the case that every spatial part of ChocolateMilk37 has Milk36 among its constituents. constituents means, rather, that every part of its first argument has some part of the second argument among its components.
label: Spatially Intrinsic Arg
spatiallyIntrinsicArg

comment:
An instance of IrreflexiveBinaryPredicate and TransitiveBinaryPredicate. (#$sihmsWithCommonSuperExpressionMutuallySupportive SIHM-1 SIHM-2) means that the instances SIHM-1 and SIHM-2 of SemanticInterpretationHypothesisMicrotheory are mutually supportive, in a very specific way: Given three instances of LinguisticExpressionPeg PEG, SUB-PEG-1 and SUB-PEG-2 such that (properSubExpressions PEG SUB-PEG-1) and (properSubExpressions PEG SUB-PEG-2) where SUB-PEG-1 and SUB-PEG-2 are not sub-expressions of each other, and SIHM-1 and SIHM-2 contain hypothesized semantic interpretations of SUB-PEG-1 and SUB-PEG-2, (#$sihmsWithCommonSuperExpressionMutuallySupportive SIHM-1 SIHM-2) holds just in case SIHM-1 and SIHM-2 distinguish themselves from other pairs of interpretations of parts of PEG by virtue of a semantic closeness between them that could help form a sense of what PEG is about.

For example, if PEG is an occurrence of the sentence, "Oil and other natural resources will increase in value as the earth's population continues to grow," and among the various interpretation hypotheses for the sub-expressons of PEG are SIHM-1, that "oil" in this context maps to Petroleum_CrudeOil; SIHM-2, that "oil" maps to ArtistsOilPaint, and SIHM-3, that "natural resources" maps to NaturalResourceType, then because (isa Petroleum_CrudeOil NaturalResourceType), SIHM-1 and SIHM-2 count as mutually supportive, whereas SIHM-2 and SIHM-3 do not.
Mx4rvWHsNJwpEbGdrcN5Y29ycA: Sihms Mutually Supportive Concept Referred To In Distinct Ways

sihmsMutuallySupportive-ConceptReferredToInDistinctWays

comment: A binary predicate used to relate a Situation to sentences that are true because of (or: made true by) the situation. We can think of Situations, in this light, as the states of affairs or `parts' of the world that are the truth-makers of sentences. For example, (situationIsSuchThat MeetingInTheOvalOfficeOnJune12 (postureOfAnimal BillClinton SittingPosture)) allows us to characterize the state of affairs in the Oval Office on June 12 as a particular situation that `includes' the state of affairs that Bill Clinton is sitting. This is not the same as holdsIn, at least given the intended meaning of holdsIn. For one thing, it doesn't presuppose that situations must have temporal extent throughout which something holds. Note that if (situationIsSuchThat SIT P) and P entails Q, then (situationIsSuchThat SIT Q). So, any situation in which Clinton is sitting in the Oval Office is a situation in which an Individual is sitting in the Oval Office.
label: situation such that
situationIsSuchThat

After TRANSFER, RECIP understands or conceives of the information transferred in TRANSFER; Cyc does NOT conclude that s/he knows the information or counts it among his/her beliefs, because RECIP might not believe it. In receiving the information transferred, RECIP may be acting intentionally or unintentionally. Note that if the communication event used in the first argument slot of this predicate is a CommunicationAct_Single and the recipient of the information was intended to receive the information by the originator of the communication event (see communicationTarget) then recipientOfInfo_Intended should probably be used instead of recipientOfInfo. label: Net Decreasing Function On Arg
netDecreasingFunctionOnArg
comment: (A function characterizing predicate used to describe the behavior of a FixedArityFunction. (netDecreasingFunctionOnArg FN N) is true iff the following conditional holds. Let L-TERM be the result returned by the FixedArityFunction FN on a tuple of arguments where H-ARG is the Nth argument. Let H-TERM be the result returned by FN on the same set of arguments save that the Nth argument is replaced with L-ARG, and suppose (greaterThan H-ARG L-ARG): then (greaterThan H-TERM L-TERM). In the vernacular, (#$netIncreasingFunctionOnAf FN N) means that the value returned by FN decreases as the value of the Nth argument supplied to FN increases, the other argument values remaining constant.

(spatiallyIntersectingEntryFormatInArgs PRED N) means that, for any particular way of fixing the other arguments to PRED besides the Nth, for any two spatial things such that if either one is taken as the Nth argument to PRED, those spatial things must be such that they spatially intersect with one another (seespatiallyIntersects). That is, if the sequences <... ARGN ...> and <... ARGN-PRIME ...> differ at most in their Nth items and both (PRED ... ARGN ...) and (PRED ... ARGN-PRIME ...) hold, then if (argIsa PRED N SpatialThing) then (spatiallyIntersects ARGN ARGN-PRIME) holds (i.e. (not (spatiallyDisjoint ARGN ARGN-PRIME)) holds).

(relationCategoryType RELATION COLLECTION) means that any instance of RELATION must have at least one argument place such that the argIsa for that argument place is COLLECTION or one of its specs. This is useful for defining relation types whose instances, by definition, must have some collection as one or more of its argument type restrictions, but where the definition of the predicate type places no restrictions on argument placement, i.e. is agnostic about N for (argIsa PRED N REQUIREDCOLLECTION). For instance, (relationCategoryType MetaPredicate CycLExpression) means that for any instance of MetaPredicate, MPRED, (argIsa MPRED N CycLExpression) must be true for some positive integer although membership in the predicate category is not dependent on the value of N.

PRODUCT is distinct from the instances of ComputerProgramCopy which are programCopies of PROGRAM by virtue of being 'productized.' This often entails being packaged. label: Product Version Of Program
productVersionOfProgram

comment: (laterThanOrCooriginatingWith DATE1 DATE2) means that the CycL date DATE1 starts no earlier than the CycL date DATE2. This is currently defined in terms of laterThan with a one second granularity -- DATE1 is strictly later than the date that is one second before DATE2.
label: Later Than Or Cooriginating With
laterThanOrCooriginatingWith
Network Has Security Environment
networkHasSecurityEnvironment
comment: (networkHasSecurityEnvironment NETWORK ENVIRON) means that the instance of ComputerNetwork, NETWORK, has a security environment described by ENVIRON.

An EquivalenceRelation (q.v.) and the most general NumericComparisonPredicate (q.v.). numericallyComparable relates any two ScalarIntervals that can be compared in terms of less than, equal to, or greater than. (numericallyComparable SCALAR1 SCALAR2) means that one of SCALAR1 and SCALAR2 is greaterThanOrEqualTo the other. SCALAR1 and SCALAR2 must either both be NumericIntervals (q.v.) or both be MeasurableQuantity(ies); in the latter case they must also both be measurable in the same units (see UnitOfMeasure and interconvertibleUnits).

For example, (numericallyComparable 5 500) and (numericallyComparable (Meter 1) (Mile 7)); but 5 and (Meter 1) are not numerically comparable.
label: Numerically Comparable
numericallyComparable

comment: (shortTermDrugTherapySideEffects THERAPY-TYPE CONDITION) means that the instance of PhysiologicalConditionType CONDITION is one of the possible side-effects of undergoing THERAPY-TYPE, a specialization of DrugTherapy, for a short period of time.

comment: (queryingContextForTEP TEP MT) means that MT, a TextualEntailmentProblemSolvingContext, is the context in which background content should be asserted and queries should be asked for the TextualEntailmentProblem TEP.

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function ShortTermFn. (shortTerm X (ShortTermFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.

shortTerm

nextHigherOrder

comment: (proposingAgents PROPOSAL AGENT) means that the intelligent agent (c.f., IntelligentAgent) AGENT is one of the agents proposing the instance of Proposal PROPOSAL.

proposingAgents

(reliabilityOfAssertion_UnknownSource ASSERTION RELIABILITY) holds just in case there exists some source of ASSERTION and that source is known to be reliable to degree RELIABILITY. This predicate is useful for SKSI mappings of databases that assign the links in their database various degrees of "reliability", but don't actually specify the source.

comment: (onTraversal ARG1 TRAV) means that ARG1 is located along the Traversal TRAV. ARG1 could be a moving object or a stationary point (see the more specific predicate pointOnTraversal). For example, if I drive from Austin to Dallas to LA and back to Dallas, and if the Traversal TRAV here is characterized by the PathChain 'Austin--Dallas--LA--Dallas, then all Austin, Dallas and LA are qualified to be the ARG1 in (onTraversal ARG1 TRAV), and so are my car and me. Let TRAV be (TraversalFn (TheList X(1) PATH(1) ... X(n) PATH(n) X(n+1))). Then (onTraversal A TRAV) holds if and only if there is a k = 1, ..., n such that (onPath A PATH(k)) holds.

onTraversal

This is in effect saying that the two terms are close enough in meaning that TERM1 should be treated exactly like TERM2 for the purpose of web searching. A good example of this is the distinction between CalendarSummer and SummerSeason. This is a distinction which is fine to have in the KB, but irrelevant for searching the World Wide Web.

comment:
A ShapePredicate (q.v.) and "restricted specialization" (see genlPredsWRTTypes) of isa that relates a spatial object to a collection of things having (at least approximately) the same shape (see SpatialThingTypeByShape). (objectShapeType OBJECT SHAPETYPE) means that SHAPETYPE characterizes OBJECT's shape (at some level of generality). If SHAPETYPE is a collection of things all having the same dimensionality as OBJECT (see SpatialThingTypeByNumberOfDimensions), OBJECT might actually be an instance of SHAPETYPE; but if SHAPETYPE is a collection of things all having the a different dimensionality than OBJECT, OBJECT can only approximate the shape in question.

For example, (objectShapeType MyCrystalBall SphericalSolid) holds because my crystal ball is a solid sphere. On the other hand (objectShapeType MyMousePad Rectangle), while true, only means that my mouse pad is roughly rectangular in shape, as a three-dimensional object like a mousepad can't literally have a two-dimensional shape.

When making a ground-atomic assertion to the Knowledge Base regarding a particular object's shape it is normally advisable to use the most specific applicable SpatialThingTypeByShape available. But note that the predicate objectShapeType itself implies no such thing; a more-inclusive shape-type will always characterize an object whenever a (correlatively) less-inclusive shape-type does. Thus, (objectShapeType MyMousePad Polygon) holds if the second example above does.

See also the nearly corresponding type-level function CommonShapeFn.
label: shape
objectShapeType

comment:
A MetaKnowledgePredicate that is used to express that certain pragmatic preconditions on a given rule are satisfied. The predicate takes as arguments a list of CycL variables and an asserted rule (see CycLRuleAssertion) in which those variables occur "free". At the EL ("epistemological level"), pragmaticallyNormal sentences are not asserted as GAFs, but appear instead as the antecedents of system-generated implies rules. For a given sequence of values for the respective variables VAR1, ..., VARn, (pragmaticallyNormal (TheList VAR1 ... VARn) RULE) means that any pragmatic preconditions placed on RULE's being used by the Cyc inference engine (see pragmaticRequirement) are satisfied with respect to those values.

Let's make this more precise and explicit. A pragmatic precondition for a rule is written like so:

(pragmaticRequirement CONDITION RULE)

and gets canonicalized into a rule involving pragmaticallyNormal like so:

(implies (pragmaticallyNormal (TheList VAR1 ... VARn) RULE) CONDITION),

where VAR1, ..., VARn are all and only the variables that occur free in RULE and thus include all (and possibly only) the variables that occur free in CONDITION (i.e. as RULE and CONDITION explicitly appear in the KB browser, without consideration of their having "implicit" initial universal quantifiers).

The above pragmaticallyNormal rule is used in inference as though it were a constraint rule. If CONDITION does not hold for a given sequence of values <VAL1, ..., VALn> for its variables <VAR1, ..., VARn>, then those values are not "pragmatically normal" for RULE; and hence inference will not proceed using <VAL1, ..., VALn> with RULE.

The effect of the foregoing is that any asserted rule RULE is implicitly treated by the Cyc inference engine as if it had the form

(implies (pragmaticallyNormal (TheList VAR1 ... VARn) RULE) RULE)

(with VAR1, ..., VARn as described above).

This convention allows the logical content of a rule to be expressed independently of any pragmatic preconditions for its being used in inference.

Also see abnormal, which is syntactically similar and has a related interpretation that makes it roughly the complement of pragmaticallyNormal.
label: Pragmatically Normal
pragmaticallyNormal

comment: This predicate relates terms in the KB to formulas expressing KE suggestions for things of that type which do in fact apply to the term in question. (keSuggestionApplies TERM FORMULA) relates TERM to some FORMULA containing a suggestion about information that should be asserted about TERM. For instance, if some collection is partitioned it might be suggested in some formula, FORM-EX, that subsets of the collection be considered for membership in one of the partition cells. If in fact, this suggestion applies to a given subset, SUB-EX, of the collection, i.e. if it should be made a specialization of one of the partition cells, it would be the case that (keSuggestionApplies COL FORM).
label: Ke Suggestion Applies
keSuggestionApplies

comment: (mentorOf PERSON MENTOR) means that MENTOR is the mentor of PERSON, in the sense that MENTOR is a teacher or trusted counselor or advisor of PERSON.

comment: knowsLoginInformationForAccount is a predicate that relates an instance of IntelligentAgent to an instance of ComputerAccount. (knowsLoginInformationForAccount AGENT ACCOUNT) means that AGENT knows a passwordForAccount and a usernameForAccount for some UserAccount ACCOUNT on a computational system.

This predicate relates spatial paths to the spatial regions they intersect. (pathIntersectsRegion PATH REGION) means that some segment of PATH is in REGION. More precisely, there is some subPaths SUBPATH of PATH such that SUBPATH is pathInsideRegion REGION. PATH might be wholly contained in REGION or might continue beyond REGION in one or both directions.(Note that it is possible in principle for a path to spatiallyIntersects a region and yet not be related to it by pathIntersectsRegion, say if only part of the edge of the path overlaps the region.) For more specific predicates, see pathIntoRegion, pathInsideRegion, pathThroughRegion, pathPassesThroughRegion, pathEndsInRegion, and pathDividesRegion.
label: path intersecting region
pathIntersectsRegion

mvpAwardForTeam

packetsTransferred

(molecularSubComponents CHEMICAL_OBJECT MOLECULAR_COMPONENT) means that MOLECULAR_COMPONENT is a connected part of CHEMICAL_OBJECT (either an instance of Molecule or a larger part of a molecule). molecularSubComponents is a typedGenlPreds of physicalParts, used for relating a molecule (or portion of a molecule) with molecular subcomponents that are deemed to be of interest. Subcomponents may be polyatomic or they may be atoms, and are to be distinguished on the grounds that they are part of the molecule in question in virtue of ionic or covalent bonds.

comment: (newDiscourseReferentInUDS UDS PEG) means that PEG is a discourse entity introduced in the discourse by the utterance to which UDS corresponds.

comment: (keySuborganizations BIG-ORG LITTLE-ORG) holds just in case LITTLE-ORG is a key suborganization of BIG-ORG. This predicate is similar to #$keyMembers except it deals with suborganizations of an organization instead of its members. For example, (keySuborganizations #$InternationalFrontForJihadAgainstJewsAndCrusaders #$JihadMovement) holds because the terrorist group #$JihadMovement is a key suborganization of #$InternationalFrontForJihadAgainstJewsAndCrusaders.
label: key suborganization
keySuborganizations

comment: An assertion of the form (situationFallsUnderStage SIT TEMP-STAGE) is used to relate an instance of Situation SIT to an instance of TemporalStageSpecification TEMP-STAGE. TEMP-STAGE is an element in the representation of some type of Situation (let's call it SUPER-TYPE). This predicate will hold if (1) SIT is a subsituation of an instance of SUPER-TYPE and (2) SIT's type (let's call it SIT-TYPE) is covered only by TEMP-STAGE (stageCoversSubSitTypeUniquely (q.v.)). The above assertion will be used for reasoning about the temporal relations that hold between SIT and other individual subsituations of the same instance of SUPER-TYPE. NOTE: If SIT-TYPE is associated with more than one TemporalStageSpecification for SUPER-TYPE (such that only stageCoversSubSitType holds between TEMP-STAGE and SIT-TYPE), additional reasoning would be required to associate SIT with the correct TemporalStageSpecification through an assertion using situationFallsUnderStage.
label: Situation Falls Under Stage
situationFallsUnderStage

comment: (pipeAbuts-DeadEnd PIPE OBJECT) means that the generic pipe PIPE abuts and ends at OBJECT, but that any fluid flow is blocked at that point (effectively a dead end) and cannot pass through the junction to or from OBJECT.
label: Pipe Abuts Dead End
pipeAbuts-DeadEnd

shootSystemTypeOfType

pipeEndsAtCavity

comment: (negotiators NEGOTIATION AGENT) means that AGENT participates, deliberately, as a negotiating party, in the negotiating event (instance of Negotiating) NEGOTIATION. The intent is that negotiators be broad in some respects, yet narrow in others. Consider the negotiations that occurred in the Spring of 1998 with the goal of producing an agreement between Unionist and Republican factions in Northern Ireland. Assuming the existence of appropriate constants, these would be correct assertions: (negotiators <the negotiation> <the Unionist faction>), (negotiators <the negotiation> <the Republican faction>), since the two mentioned factions were the parties seeking to reach an agreement in the negotiations. It would also be correct to say (negotiators <the negotiations> MartinMcGuinness), since McGuinness acted as a representative of one of the negotiating factions. However, although in an informal sense the United States and its representative, George Mitchell, acted as 'negotiators', by playing the role of promoting progress in the negotiations, both the following would be incorrect assertions: (negotiators <the negotiations> UnitedStatesOfAmerica), (negotiators <the negotiations> GeorgeMitchell). To describe the role the US and Sen. Mitchell played in the negotiations, use mediators.
label: negotiator
negotiators

comment: (physicalCopies COPY1 COPY2) means that COPY1 and COPY2 are numerically distinct physical copies of the same thing or one is a copy of the other. If they are information bearing objects, then they contained and conveyed the same information as the original at the time the copy was made. COPY1 and COPY2 are not necessarily physically (type) identical but might have changed in different ways. For example, records or photographs may be scratched, a copy of a book may be missing a page, identical twins have developed differently so may be more or less similar in appearance at the present moment, etc.

comment: (massNumberOfAtom ATOM NUM) is true iff ATOM is an instance of Atom with a mass number of NUM. The mass number of an atom is the sum of protons and neutrons in the nucleus of an atom of X. All atoms of a particular instance of ElementStuffTypeByNumberOfProtons have the same number of protons in the nucleus (expressed as the atomicNumber of the element). Isotopes of an element (cf. IsotopeFn) have a different number of neutrons. Thus the number of neutrons in an atom of X (where X an element or isotope) equals: the mass number of the atom minus the atomic number of X. Isotopes are identified by the mass number of their atoms: e.g. (IsotopeFn Carbon 14).

comment: (sinkNodeInSystem X SYS) means that X is a sink node in the Semi_DirectedPathSystem SYS, i.e., a node to which all links attached to it come 'in', and from which no such links go 'out'. A sink node X in SYS is a node in SYS such that X is on some links but no loops in SYS, and such that each link in SYS that X is on is a link directed to X from another node. Another way to put this is that X is a node in SYS that is neither on any loop in SYS, nor an isolated node in SYS, nor a node from which a link in SYS is directed. See loopInSystem, isolatedNodeInSystem and linkFromToInSystem.

comment: (mtSubsetAbstractionLevel MT COLLECTION) means that when reasoning in (or with) the context MT, (instances of) classes of objects at about the level of abstraction indicated by COLLECTION should be attended to, or taken into account. If you consider the knowledge base as a lattice of abstract concepts arranged in a hierarchical structure via the subset/superset relation (genls), then the further `up' the hierarchy you go from COLLECTION, the less likely it is that (instances of) these classes should be used in inferencing. (Instances of) classes may also become less worth attending to as you go `down' the hierarchy (although it's hard to see how this could be true in a system with class-property inheritance). See also mtPartonomicAbstractionLevel.
label: Mt Subset Abstraction Level
mtSubsetAbstractionLevel

comment:
A binary #$IntangibleObjertPredicate. (lawProscribesActType LAW ACTTYPE) means that LAW prohibits any agent subject to it (see subjectToCOC) from performing instances of ACTTYPE. This of course does not imply that no such acts are performed, since laws are sometimes violated.

For example, (lawProscribesActType StealingIsIllegal Stealing) means that the law StealingIsIllegal prohibits stealing.

See also lawPrescribesActType and agentProhibitsActType.
label: Law Proscribes Act Type
lawProscribesActType

comment:
(maximalConsistentSubsets SET SUBSET) means that:

1. SETand SUBSET are sets of collections,
2. SUBSET is a subset of SET,
3. no element of SUBSET is disjoint with any other element of SUBSET,
4. every element of the complement of SUBSET with respect to SET is disjoint with some element of SUBSET.

This predicate is not functional in either argument position.
label: Maximal Consistent Subsets
maximalConsistentSubsets

means that the population density of Cucamonga is low.
