comment: (paCustomerIndicatedTopic PRSN TOPIC) means that in the Product Advisor interface, TheCustomer has stated she is interested in gift suggestions for Person PRSN related to TOPIC. This predicate is used to track TheCustomer's stated preference about which aspect of PRSN's life is to serve as a jumping off point for clarificatory questions. These followup questions aim at learning more about PRSN in order to make relevant gift suggestions. For example, (paCustomerIndicatedTopic TheRecipient HobbyActivity) means that TheCustomer has stated she is interested in gift suggestions related to TheRecipient's HobbyActivitys. In contrast, use explicitlyIndicatedProduct to assert that TheCustomer has stated she is interested in suggestions about an instance of ProductType.

comment: slotDefinition(S F(X)) defines slot S as being equivalent to function F(X). In other words, when given a unit U, the value on U.S = F(U). So, for example, (slotDefinition physicalMemorySize (CombineFn PlusFn rAMSize rOMSize)).

(obstacleBlocks AGT OBS) means that the obstacle OBS blocks AGT in some manner, and that AGT is not able to overcome OBS by circumventing OBS. For instance, if (obstacleBlocks TankCompany001 AlpMountainRange) is true, then TankCompany001 is not able to pass through AlpsMountainRange and also it is not possible to go around in an effective manner.

comment: A specialization of properSubSituations and subEvents (qq.v.). This predicate relates events to further events which are their proper sub-events. (properSubEvents EVENT SUBEVENT) means that the Event SUBEVENT is a part of the Event EVENT, a complete description of EVENT would have to involve a description of SUBEVENT, and SUBEVENT is not identical to EVENT itself. For example, an event in which a car is being parallel-parked might be an event in which a person turning a steering wheel is a proper sub-event. See also properSubEventTypes.
label: Proper Sub Events
properSubEvents

comment:
An instance of #$GeneralizedQuantifier-MonotoneIncreasing. (many SETORCOL1 SETORCOL2) means that many things are instances of both SETORCOL1 and SETORCOL2. What counts as "many" can vary greatly with context; thus it is difficult to give this quantifier a precise definition. However, we can pin down certain of its logical features, e.g.: 
(transitiveViaArg many subsetOf 2).
It is also important to note that many is the contradictory predicate (see contradictoryPreds) of few (q.v.).

comment: (muchGreaterThan LARGE SMALL) says that the ScalarInterval LARGE is much greater than the ScalarInterval SMALL. It is important to keep in mind that the notion of "much" is relative to some scale, and so assertions using this predicate should be carefully placed in the right context. comment:
The most general predicate for relating a relation RELATION to a collection COLL that the relation directly invokes, where "directly invokes" has a very specific definition. (relationInvokesType RELATION COLL) iff either one of two conditions holds.

First: RELATION has a nearestArgIsa or nearestArgGenl constraint to COLL; this, by convention, is an explicit invocation of COLL by RELATION. For example, since (nearestArg2Isa actionMotives Motive), (relationInvokesTypeDerivatively actionMotives Motive) holds, since actionMotives has an explicit argIsa constraint of Motive.

Second: RELATION is an instance of Predicate that, by its very definition, is such that from a closed sentence of the form, (RELATION . ARGS) one can conclude for some predicate PREDICATE (PREDICATE . PRED-ARGS) where PREDICATE has either an argIsa or argGenl of COLL. For example, (relationInvokesTypeDerivatively agentHasMotiveForAction Motive) is true, not because agentHasMotiveForAction has an explicit argument constraint of Motive, but because by the very definition of agentHasMotiveForAction, (agentHasMotiveForAction AGENT ACTION) means that there exists MOTIVE, such that (agentsActionHasMotive AGENT ACTION MOTIVE), where (isa MOTIVE Motive) due to the fact that (arg3Isa agentsActionHasMotive Motive). This, by convention, is an implicit invocation of COLL. Typically, in the case of implicit invocation, RELATION will be an instance of RuleMacroPredicate.
label: Relation Invokes Type
relationInvokesType

comment:
A CoexistingObjectsPredicate and specialization of usualLocationOfObject that relates a person or other sort of animal to a constructed shelter in which s/he/it lives or resides.

(residesInDwelling RESIDENT SHELTER) means that RESIDENT resides in SHELTER. That is, SHELTER is the place where RESIDENT usually sleeps, spends much of its time, lays its eggs; a place it cleans and maintains and repairs; a place it defends against intrusion., etc.

A person or animal might reside in more than one dwelling at a given time. For example, a person might residesInDwelling some tent during a camping trip, and at the same time it would still be true that she residesInDwelling her apartment or house. Note that the dwelling in which a person residesInDwelling is not necessarily her legal domicile, though of course it often will be. Note also that residesInDwelling does not subsume parasitical or symbiotic relationships, in which one animal lives in or on another. The more general predicate objectFoundInLocation would be the appropriate one, for example, for a case of a flea living on a dog. See also occupants and residesInRegion.
label: residing

comment: (qaValidationForts FORT1 FORT2) means that FORT2 is a concept that validates the proper name FORT3 interpretation of a substring STRING in a query submitted to the QueryAugmentationApplication whenever FORT3 is a known instance of FORT1. Validation is only required if STRING is ambiguous with respect to the QueryAugmentationApplication. For example (qaValidationForts Movie_CW Actor) validates the Big_TheMovie interpretation of the string `big' in the query `big actor', under the assumption that the substring `actor' maps on the constant Actor. qaValidationForts assertions are assumed to represent complete knowledge about what validates a proper name interpretation of a QueryAugmentationApplication query substring. The intended effect is to disallow the Big_TheMovie interpretation of the string `big' in a query such as `big boats' where no other substring in the query maps to any validating FORTs for any of the collections of which Big_TheMovie is a member.

This is a different notion from the information structure (c.f. infoStructureOfCW) of a work; a particular List_CW, for example, might have an info-structure that consists of the complete sequence of characters that were used in composing it. That list's *mathematical* structure, on the other hand, is a mathematical Tuple (indeed, a List) that consists in the ordering of items referred to by the string-sequences that make up the info-structure of that list. Though a given work might undergo change, and so have different a different mathematical structure at different times, it cannot have more than one structure at any given point.

comment:
An ActorSlot and a specialization of objectMoving (q.v.) that is used to specify a focal object that is moving in a particular MovementEvent. (primaryObjectMoving MOVE OBJECT) means that OBJECT is in motion at some point during the MovementEvent MOVE and this movement is focal in MOVE.

OBJECT moves from the fromLocation to the toLocation. OBJECT's motion in MOVE may be translational, rotational, or some combination of these. OBJECT may be a solid (such as an animal, an automobile, or a tennis ball) or a fluid (such as lava flowing or a warm air mass rising) -- but must be PartiallyTangible. If a Group of objects is moving along the same trajectory, that Group, each subGroups, and each member of that GROUP is a primaryObjectMoving in the movement. An individual part of a primaryObjectMoving may be but is not necessarily an objectMoving in MOVE. An object contained by a primaryObjectMoving is generally, but not always, also a primaryObjectMoving in the same event. Other objects moving in the MovementEvent are referred to by the more general predicate, objectMoving. A transporter which follows a separate Trajectory (e.g. a Ladle) or a conveyor which engages in a different form of motion (e.g. a rotating ConveyorBelt that translates a load) is not a primaryObjectMoving in the conveying event. Any objectMoving in a particular event is a primaryObjectMoving in one or more subEvents.
label: primary moving object
primaryObjectMoving

comment: A SubEventPredicate that is a specialization of both properSubEvents and lastProperSubSituations (qq.v.). (#$lastProperSubEvents EVENT END) means that END is a final part of EVENT. That is, END is a proper subevent of EVENT that starts after EVENT starts and ends exactly when EVENT ends. Also, END should be something that it would seem intuitively correct (in the context in question) to describe as "the last part" of EVENT. Typically, END doesn't start until at least halfway through (i.e. the temporal mid-point of) the occurring of EVENT. Note that more than one event might be considered a last part of a given event; for example, either the ninth inning or the last play of the ninth inning could be considered the last subevent of a baseball game. See also #$firstProperSubEvents.
label: completion
lastSubEvents

comment: (specificationFulfilled SIT SPEC) means that the Situation SIT satisfies the NormativeSpecification SPEC. Instances of NormativeSpecification describe types of Situation, usually quite specifically. An assertion of this amounts to saying that an individual event satsifies the description represented by SPEC. As an example, Joe can imagine having his apartment be clean. If it turns out that his roommate cleans it, then that particular NormativeSpecification is satisfied by the fact that the apartment is cleaned.

The formula (mainColorOfObject ?OBJ ?COL) means that the PartiallyTangible ?OBJ is almost entirely colored with the Color ?COL. For example, a BrownBear may have green eyes and white claws, but we would still say that the bear is brown. Therefore, (mainColorOfObject BrownBear BrownColor) would be true. An example where it is NOT appropriate to use this predicate is to describe a Zebra. Since a Zebra is roughly equally black and white, we would not say that it is primarily either of those colors. In this case, it would be better to use objectHasColor. One should think of the expressions of the form 'The OBJECT is COLOR' when using this predicate. For example, even though an apple may have a brown stem and a green leaf, we would still say 'The apple is red'. Contrarily, we would NOT say 'That zebra is black'. Likewise, if we had a shirt that was 49% red and 51% green, we would NOT say that the color of that shirt is green. If we had a shirt that was green with a small, white insignia on the pocket, we WOULD, in this case, say that the mainColorOfObject, this shirt, is green. See also objectHasColor and uniformColorOfObject.
label: Main Color Of Object
mainColorOfObject

comment: (operatesInRegion AGENT REGION) means that AGENT performs (at least once) a task central to her/its job function or group mission in REGION. Regex File Match
regexFileMatch
comment: A text-processing predicate used to indicate a match between a 'regular expression template' and a string of characters the occcurs within a computer file. (regexFileMatch REGEX COMPFILE) means that the RegularExpression template (or 'regex') REGEX matches some substring within the computer file COMPFILE. It allows for 'wildcard characters' and other regular expression features in the template. The rules for what characters to use in the regex, and what constitutes a valid match, depend on the particular regular expression matcher being used. (Regular expressions are used for matching in the GREP, EGREP, AWK, VI, TCL, Emacs, PERL and PYTHON programs.) Some regex features are common to all such programs, including these: . [...] [^...] char ? * + ^ $ \< \> | (...) \1,\2,\3,... Some other features vary. This predicate assumes that the PERL specification is used for regular expression matching. Briefly: The period matches 'any character'. Square brackets match a class of characters, those listed, possibly with ranges like A-Z or a-z or 1-8. Square brackets with a caret-character as the first included character match the class of characters other than those listed between the brackets. Backslash-character means the following special character is directly matched and is not treated as a special character. Caret matches the position of the start-of-line. Dollar-sign matches the position at the end-of-line. \< matches any start of word. \> matches any end-of-word. Parentheses group whatever they enclose. A character or group followed by a question-mark is optional; it matches zero or one occurence of that group or charater. A character or group followed by an asterisk matches any number of repetitions that group or character, including zero. A character or group followed by a plus-sign matches one or more repetitions of that group or character. A vertical bar | separates alternative matches -- either may succeed. \1,\2,\3, etc. are backreference variables to which each matched group is assigned in order, and they will match later occurrences of the assigned group. For further details, see standard documentation for regular expressions or for PERL. See also regexStringMatch.

comment:
A binary predicate that is used to associate a given ScalarInterval with a rank (represented by an integer), as determined by the complexity of the dimensional analysis (see unitTypeDimensionalAnalysis) relevant to that scalar.

(scalarDimensionalRank SCALAR RANK) means that SCALAR has rank RANK, where RANK is determined as follows. If SCALAR is a NumericInterval (q.v.) then RANK is 0. If SCALAR is a MeasurableQuantity measurable in units of a FundamentalUnitType (q.v.) then RANK is 1. If SCALAR is a quantity measurable in units of a derived unit-type whose dimensional analysis is: 

  (TheSet
    (TheList UNITTYPE-1 EXPONENT-1)
    (TheList UNITTYPE-2 EXPONENT-2)
    ...
    (TheList UNITTYPE-n EXPONENT-n))

then RANK is the sum of the absolute values of all of the EXPONENT-i (1 <= i <= n). Otherwise (e.g. if SCALAR is a NonNumericScalarQuantity), it is not associated with any rank.

For example, the rank of (Meter 5) is 1, as Meter is a UnitOfDistance, which is a FundamentalUnitType. And the rank of (MilesPerHour 25) is 2, as MilesPerHour is a UnitOfSpeed, which has the analysis: 

  (TheSet
    (TheList UnitOfDistance 1)
    (TheList UnitOfTime -1)) ;

and 1 + |-1| = 2. Similarly, the volume (CubicFoot 18) has rank 3.
label: Scalar Dimensional Rank
scalarDimensionalRank

OBJECT exists before EVENT, is directly involved in EVENT, and persists after EVENT (accordingly, this predicate has as genlPreds both preActors and postActors). The change which OBJECT undergoes is internal or intrinsic; this predicate is not used for extrinsic changes, such as changes in location, orientation, ownership, or status. comment: An assertion of the form (normativeSpecificationParts WHOLE PART) is used to relate an instance of NormativeSpecification WHOLE to an instance of NormativeSpecification PART where the relationship is a whole to part relationship. This is a distinct relationship from derivativeSpecificationOf, in that PART refers directly to the content of WHOLE, whereas a derivative specification is indirectly related to the second specification. For example, consider the project of killing two people, where that project is carried out for the purposes of winning an inheritance. The specification to kill both people is derived from the specification of winning the inheritance. However, if I have two separate plans for killing the people, each plan is part of the larger specification. normativeSpecificationParts is used when completing one of the part-specifications partially realizes the state of affairs which is the content of the whole-specification. derivativeSpecificationOf is used when the content of the derived NormativeSpecification sets the stage for realizing the content of the more fundamental NormativeSpecification More formally, normativeSpecificationParts is used to relate an logical entailment relation of the content of the part-motive by the content of the whole-specification. The contents of the source-specification and derived-specifications are related by knowledge that realizing the content of the derived-specification has causal implications for the realization of the content of the source-specification.
label: Normative Specification Parts
normativeSpecificationParts

comment:
The most general instance of BinaryRolePredicate; that collection's commonGenlPreds. This predicate relates situations (see Situation) to the tangible and intangible Individuals involved in those situations.

(situationConstituents SIT INDIVIDUAL) means that INDIVIDUAL is a constituent of, or plays some role in, SIT. The role played by INDIVIDUAL might be almost anything, as long as it's "intrinsic" to SIT. Thus to perform, to be changed in the course of, to be information conveyed in, or to be an abstractum the instantiating of which figures in a given situation is to be a constituent of that situation; but to predict, to be a cause or effect of, or to know about a situation is not sufficient to be a constituent. Arguably, INDIVIDUAL must in part constitute SIT, in the modal sense that SIT (that very situation) would not have occurred or obtained had INDIVIDUAL not played the role it did.

An important specialization of situationConstituents is actors (q.v.), the most general predicate relating Events to their participants.
label: participant in situation
situationConstituents

(localConditionOnReferentExpression EXPRESSION-PEG EXPRESSION-TYPE) means that (isa EXPRESSION-PEG EXPRESSION-TYPE) is a provisional constraint on the referential expression EXPRESSION-PEG that we can extract from the current discourse state. Properties constraining a discourse-referent expression can be either agreement features expressed as LinguisticExpressionTypes. The properties of the referents themselves, i.e., the collections of which they are instances, can be expressed with localConditionOnDiscourseReferent (q.v.).

comment: (possessiveRelation OWNER CONTENT) captures a very underspecified possessive relationship between OWNER and CONTENT. This possession may be inalienable, as in 'Paula's big nose', or alienable, as in 'Clinton's cigars', relational as in 'Caesar's wife', situational as in' 'Monica's death by chocolate' or 'Hillary's running for office', or just downright ambiguous as in 'DuMaurier's death in venice'. The idea is that such precise relationships (all of which are in some sense 'possessive', metaphoric or otherwise) are the products or situated reasoning and common-sense knowledge; these relationships cannot be inferred by lexical or grammatical means during language analysis.

A binary IntangibleObjectPredicate that relates intangible "information stores" (see AspatialInformationStore) to the things they are "about". (propositionalInfoAbout AIS THING) means that the AIS is or contains propositional information about THING. For instance, AIS might be a Microtheory with assertions concerning THING or a TextualPCW containing information about THING. This relation constitutes a kind of "intentionality" in the philosophers' sense (see e.g. IntentionalMentalSituation), though some would argue that it is only an indirect or derived sort of intentionality in that it always presupposes an underlying intention on the part of some agent(s).

Although the notion of a written text or other sort of conceptual work being (propositionally) "about" something is a completely familiar one -- it is regularly appealed to in everyday discourse as well as in academic studies pertaining to meaning or interpretation -- giving a precise analysis of the notion (in the form of necessary and sufficient conditions, e.g.) is a notoriously difficult task, shot-through with controversy. Still, a couple of non-contentious points can be made in this direction. First, it is clear that the information in question must be sufficiently specific to the thing it is "about". That is, in order for AIS to "contain propositional information about" THING it is _not_ sufficient that AIS merely involve general information about the elements of some collection (or set or class) to which THING belongs, but must involve some way of singling-out THING, e.g. by mentioning THING by name or containing a description that uniquely applies to THING. For example, the sentence 'Dogs are carnivores' is too general to be "about" Lassie (though it _is_ arguably about the collections Dog and Carnivore); 'Television's best-loved canine was a collie', on the other hand, is certainly about her. Second, since the information must be _propositional_ (see e.g. Proposition), it is also _not_ sufficient that AIS merely contain a term or symbol that specifies or denotes or represents THING; AIS must "say something about" THING. Thus, a mere unannotated list of the names of famous show-biz animals would _not_ be propositionally about Lassie, even though her name would undoubtedly appear on it. Finally, note that propositionalInfoAbout does _not_ insist that THING is what AIS is mainly or focally about; thus the selfsame AIS might easily be about several (even many) different things at the same time.
label: Propositional Info About
propositionalInfoAbout

THING2 must be a direct copy or derivative; it cannot be an indirect copy (a derivative of a derivative of the original). It can be a complementary 'reverse' copy or a 'negative', or an approximate or partial derivative of the original pattern. Pretty-String: paths overlapping the path of motion
comment:
An ActorSlot and specialization of genericPathway_Partial that relates a Movement_TranslationEvent to a Path_Spatial such that at least part of the movement is along part of the path. It can be used to indicate one of the paths followed in a movement event. More formally, (motionPathway_Partial MOVE PATH) means that MOVE has a trajectory (see trajectory_Complete) with a sub-trajectory in common with some subPaths of PATH.

For example, if a certain trip to Dallas from Austin is via highway I-35, this does not imply either that the whole journey is along I-35 (it also may be along driveways and side streets), or that it is along all of I-35 (which would take you from the Mexican border all the way to the Canadian border). A part of the journey is along a part of I-35.

Contrast this predicate with motionPathway_Complete, which relates a movement event to a spatial path followed throughout all of the movement.

comment: A CycInferenceDescriptorPredicate. Only if TEST returns `T' (for `True') when applied to a particular term can that term's denotatum be considered a quoted instance of COL; all terms that denote quoted instances of COL must fulfill TEST's requirements, although there may be additional requirements for denoting an instance of COL as well. However, terms asserted to be quoted instances of the collection COL using quotedIsa are exempt from fulfilling TEST's requirements. See also quotedDefnSufficient and #$quotedDefnIff.

Thus, for example (RAD-PRED POINT (Meter 5)) would mean that, in SYS, the distance from POINT to the pole is 5 meters.

See also azimuthAnglePredicate and altitudeAnglePredicate.

comment: (perceives AGENT OBJECT) means that AGENT is perceiving OBJECT. That is, AGENT is consciously aware of the presence of OBJECT via the functioning of at least one of her/his/its senses (e.g. sight, hearing, smell, etc). Precisely which tangible features of OBJECT AGENT apprehends depends in part on the sensory modality used (see the specializations of perceives). For example, if (sees AGENT OBJECT) then AGENT is aware of certain visible features of OBJECT (such as color or shape), whereas if (smells AGENT OBJECT) then AGENT apprehends certain aromatic features of OBJECT (such as its wearing L'air Du Temps perfume). Only tangible objects and situations involving such objects (see situationConstituents) -- PartiallyTangibles, PhysicalEvents, and Configurations (which are StaticSituations involving partially tangibles) -- can be perceived.
label: perception of something
perceives

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function ManyFn. (manyOf X (ManyFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.

manyOf

comment:
A specialization of pointInSystem (q.v.) that relates PathSystems (q.v.) to their "nodes". (nodeInSystem NODE SYSTEM) means that NODE is a node in SYSTEM. The nodes of SYSTEM are distinguished from its other points as follows.

(i) Every node in SYSTEM is a point in SYSTEM, but only nodes can be either end points of links (see linkBetweenInSystem), "deadend" points (see deadEndInSystem) or "isolated" points (i.e. points that are not on any link or loop; see isolatedNodeInSystem).

(ii) Each point that is not a node must be somewhere on a single link. That is, for each point POINT in SYSTEM, either (pointOnPath POINT LINK) holds for unique link LINK in SYSTEM, or POINT is a node. Thus every "intersection" point (see junctionInSystem) in SYSTEM is a node. See also NodesInSystemFn.
label: Node In System
nodeInSystem

A PropositionalAttitudeSlot and a specialization of hasFactiveEmotion and negativeInterest_Prop. (regrets AGT PROP) means that AGT regrets that PROP is true. In particular, it entails that AGT knows that PROP is true, and that AGT wishes (desires) that PROP were not true. For example,

means that Alice regrets that she has never been married. It entails that Alice knows that she has never been married, and that she wishes she had been married.

(But there are some exceptions. E.g. some Japanese Autos are fabricated in USA.) Often, a person is originallyFromRegion where they were from. (But I doubt a 25 year resident of the USA who was born 26 years ago to Anglo parents would be considered `African'.)

comment: An assertion of the form (laterStage INTER-SPEC TEMP-STAGE) is used to relate an instance of InterStageSpecification to an instance of TemporalStageSpecification. Instances of InterStageSpecification are used to provide a type-level representation of a type of Situation (let's introduce one and call it SIT-TYPE). In particular, they description the duration of time intervals that subsume or separate the subsituations of instances of SIT-TYPE. Instances of InterStageSpecification connect to the situations via this relation to a TemporalStageSpecifications. this predicate picks out the TemporalStageSpecification that covers the subsituations that are comparatively later in instances of SIT-TYPE. The later TemporalStageSpecification is picked out with the predicate earlierStage.

laterStage

comment: (mealServed HAVING-A-MEAL MEAL) means that MEAL is the instance of Meal that is acted on during HAVING-A-MEAL. That is, MEAL is the Meal that is served or otherwise provided for consumption during HAVING-A-MEAL, and which is subsequently consumed during that event. Note that MEAL need not be completely consumed during HAVING-A-MEAL -- portions may remain to be finished later or discarded. Thus, mealServed is not a specialization of consumedObject. Also, MEAL need not be served to the participants in HAVING-A-MEAL in the formal sense of ServingFoodOrDrink, since participants may fetch their own portion of MEAL themselves.

situationTopic is a very general binary relation between an instance of MentalSituation and an instance of Thing. An assertion of the form (situationTopic SIT THING) means that there is some IntelligentAgent that is a situationConstituents of the MentalSituation SIT, that agent participates in SIT, and SIT 'refers to' or 'is about' Thing. This predicate operates at a very coarse granularity for describing MentalSituations and so, is inferentially weak. Its main function is to allow for the introduction of things into a MentalSituation even if they are quite peripheral. Moreover, it does not entail that every IntelligentAgent that is a situationConstituents in SIT needs have a mental state involving THING. For instance, in a Talking event, someone might miss the part of the conversation where Spiderman was introduced. situationTopic could still be used to relate that event to Spiderman, even though there is someone involved who has no mental states about that Spiderman during that Talking event.
label: Situation Topic
situationTopic

comment: The predicate postalCodeOfAddress_NC maps a particular element of ContactLocation to a non-canonical PostalCode. The `NC' in the name stands for `non-canonical'. (postalCodeOfAddress_NC LOCATION CODE) means that the ContactLocation LOCATION has the non-canonicalized PostalCode, CODE. For example, one value for postalCodeOfAddress_NC of the Cycorp MailingLocation is `78731'. Note that this postal code as printed does not conform to the US Postal Service's recommended standard for printed ZIP codes, and so relative to this standard it is not `canonical.' Non-canonical means that CODE may not conform to the canonicalization scheme(s) used for other known postal codes for LOCATION. These other (presumed canonical) postal codes should be related to LOCATION using the predicate postalCodeOfAddress. It really only makes sense to use postalCodeOfAddress_NC in contexts (such as the LogicalTableSchemas for certain database tables) where LOCATION may have both canonical and non-canonical postal codes entered for it. In contexts where the differences between canonicalized and non-canonicalized postal codes is not an issue, just use postalCodeOfAddress. See also ContactLocation.

A binary RuleMacroPredicate that relates a SpatialThing to a type of spatial thing such that the former is spatially subsumed by something of that type. (spatiallySubsumedBy_InsType OBJ TYPE) means that there is at least one instance INST of TYPE such that (spatiallySubsumes INST OBJ) is true. For example, 
  (spatiallySubsumedBy_InsType CityOfAustinTX Country)
means that Austin is subsumed by at least one country.

entails that the Hope Diamond can fit inside a RightCylinder that is 10 centimeters high and 10 centimeters in diameter. Its truth follows from the fact that (at any given moment) the Hope is indeed subsumed by a SpaceRegion of that shape and size.

comment:
A binary MetaLanguagePredicate that can be used to state that a given argument-place of a given CycL relation-denoting expression is denotationally opaque.

(opaqueArgument REL N) means that if in a closed compound expression built from the CycL expression for REL -- i.e. a ground atomic formula (or gaf) if REL is a predicate or a closed non-atomic term (or nat) if REL is a function -- the term appearing in REL's Nth argument-place is replaced with another term having the same denotatum (or truth-value, if the term is a sentence), there is no guarantee that the resulting gaf (or nat) will itself have the same truth-value (or denotatum) as the original.

Most argument-places of most relation-denoting expressions do allow such substitutions to be made freely, and are thus denotationally transparent. For example, given that (equals Cicero Tully), the truth of (residesInRegion Cicero CityOfRomeItaly) entails the truth of (residesInRegion Tully CityOfRomeItaly). This shows that residesInRegion's first argument-place is denotationally transparent. On the other hand, if Caesar were seeking Cicero and found him then (objectFound_Definite CaesarsSearchForCicero Caesar Cicero) would be true; but (objectFound_Definite CaesarsSearchForCicero Caesar Tully) might nevertheless be false, because Caesar might not know that Tully is Cicero and thus might not realize that in finding Cicero he had found Tully. Having such a realization is a necessary condition for objectFound_Definite's holding, which shows that this relation's third argument-place is denotationally opaque.

According to one well-known semantics for denotational opacity (viz. GottlobFrege's), a term appearing in an opaque context (in most cases) denotes (not its ordinary denotatum, but) what is ordinarily its intensional meaning or sense (or Sinn, in Frege's native German).

quotedArgument (q.v.) is a specialization of opaqueArgument, and a term appearing in a quoted context is interpreted as denoting itself (rather than its usual denotatum).
label: Opaque Argument
opaqueArgument

comment:
A MetaLanguagePredicate (q.v.) that relates SubLSExpressions to their meanings: the things in the intended model of the CycL language that those terms denote, refer to, stand for, or express. (means TERM THING) means that TERM denotes, refers to, stands for, or expresses THING. TERM will often be explicitly quoted, by being wrapped in the syncategorematic quotation symbol 'Quote'. For example, the true sentence '(means (Quote Plato) Plato)' means that the CycL term 'Plato' means (denotes) the person Plato. (Thus means's first argument-place is not "implicitly quoted"; cf. quotedArgument).

But note that the first argument of means might not be quoted at all. Suppose (e.g.) that the term 'Plato' were the CycL constant most beloved of Cyclists, and that a new constant 'CyclistsFavoriteConstant' were reified and defined so as to reflect this fact. Then 'CyclistsFavoriteConstant' would denote the CycL constant 'Plato', which in turn denotes the man Plato; and so the sentence '(means CyclistsFavoriteConstant Plato)' -- which involves no quotation -- would be true.

Note finally that the sentence '(means Plato Plato)' is of course not true, as it means that the man Plato is a CycL term that denotes the man Plato, which is a patent falsehood since no man is a CycL term and no man denotes anything.

See also expresses, denotes, hasDenotatum, quotedIsa, EscapeQuote, and the shared #$NoteAboutQuotingInCycL.
label: Means (antitransitive binary predicate)
means

comment: (opTypeRequiresAgentType OP_TYPE AGENT_TYPE) means that, in the context of the assertion, a MilitaryOperation OP of type OP_TYPE requires an Agent_PartiallyTangible of type AGENT_TYPE as an 'agent resource', in the sense that an instance AGENT of AGENT_TYPE in the context will be (agentResourceInEvent OP AGENT).

comment: This predicate relates an agent to a type of object an instance of which s/he needs to obtain or possess in order to achieve or further some (unspecified) goal (as in "Pam needs a computer"). The intended sense of "needs" here is broad, ranging from matters of practical convenience to matters of life and death; see the comment on needs_Generic for a fuller account. (needs_Type AGENT OBJTYPE) means that AGENT needs an instance of OBJTYPE. The default assumption is that there is no one particular instance needed: any instance of OBJTYPE will do. (If there were a _particular_ computer that Pam needed, we could represent this using needs (q.v.) to relate her to that computer directly.) The above formula does not imply that AGENT needs OBJTYPE itself in the sense of needing a certain abstract collection qua collection, which is a dubious notion anyway. What AGENT needs an OBJTYPE for (i.e. what goal of hers it would further) and what will happen to AGENT if she fails to obtain one (e.g. whether she will die, suffer an important loss, or just be noticeably inconvenienced) are left unspecified in the above formula, though in practice they might be inferable from other assertions in the context (see e.g. needsFor). Note that needs_Type has to do with an "objective" requirement of AGENT's for an OBJTYPE, and does not entail a corresponding "felt need" on the part of AGENT. A felt need of this sort is perhaps best represented as an assertion that a given agent both knows that s/he objectively needs_Type a certain type of thing and desires that s/he obtain or possess such a thing. needs_Type does imply, though, that AGENT is at least awareOf OBJTYPEs in general. See also needs_Prop, needsToDo, #$needsToHaveAttribute, and satisfiesNeed.
label: Needs-Type
needs-Type

comment:
(roleWithEventTypeEntailsTimeIndex ROLE-PRED SIT-TYPE) holds just in case some present tense progressive version of ROLE-PRED holds in the time period picked out by the startingDate and endingDate of any instance of SIT-TYPE. For example

(roleWithEventTypeEntailsSomeTimeInTimeIndex containerUsed StorageOfSomethingInAContainer)

holds because we could create a present tense progressive version of containerUsed (call it 'currentlyContains') and that predicate would hold of the the container and contained object in the time interval picked out by the starting and ending dates of the event in question. More formally:

If

(and (containerUsed SIT CONTAINER) (isa SIT StorageOfSomethingInAContainer) (startingDate* SIT T1) (endingDate* SIT T2) (containedObject SIT OBJ)

then

(currentlyContains CONTAINER OBJ) <MT (TimeIntervalInclusiveFn T1 T2) TimePoint>

*This particular interpretation requires versions of startingDate and endingDate that correspond to the starting point and ending point of the situation in question and not just the "sometime in date" interpretation they currently employ

roleWithEventTypeEntailsTimeIndex

comment: A specialization of the predicate onPath that relates a simple path (see Path_Simple) to any point on that path. (pointOnPath POINT PATH) means that POINT is a point along PATH. That is, POINT is on PATH but cannot move along PATH (even if it could move in some other sense). It might or might not be the case that POINT, or some part of it, is a part of PATH. POINT is not a subpath (see subPaths) of PATH; it is not something that is on PATH only occasionally (such as something moving along or stopped on PATH); and it is does not have PATH as a part (e.g. Washington DC is not a point on its own Pennsylvania Avenue). Note that the relative positions of points on a path do not in general form a linear order (see TotalOrdering) unless the points and the path are part of a particular PathSystem. For example, if no path system is specified, both Austin and Texas can be veiwed as points on Interstate 35.
label: point on simple path
pointOnPath

comment: (objectLeftSide OBJECT LEFT-SIDE) relates an instance of LeftAndRightSidedObject OBJECT to the entire surfact part that is considerd the left side LEFT-SIDE. See also LeftAndRightSidedObject.

predicateForComparisonClassForFACTory

comment: linuxRedHatManPageString relates instances of #$CycSecureFORT to snippets of text from RedHat Linux man pages that document computer programs. linuxRedHatManPageString

comment: A binary RelativeLocationalPredicate that relates a (tangible or intangible) spatial thing to an intrinsic axis (if it has any). By an "intrinsic" here we mean an axis an object has either purely in virtue of its geometric shape or in virtue of some natural or conventional feature it has regarding its directional orientation. More precisely, (objectAxes OBJECT AXIS) means that either (i) AXIS is an axis of symmetry of OBJECT (see the specialization symmetricAxes) or (ii) OBJECT is an BilateralObject (q.v.) and AXIS passes through the centers (see centroidOfObject) of two if its opposing sides (see the specialization bilateralAxes).
label: Object Axes
objectAxes

comment:
A CoexistingObjectsPredicate that is a generalization of both agreeingAgents and obligatedAgents (qq.v.). The predicate normativelyBoundAgents relates a normative specification to any agent that it "normatively constrains" in some way or other. Thus, it relates an agreement to the agents who are party to it, a proposal to the agent who proposed it, an obligation to the agents who are subject to it, and so on.

More precisely: where NORM is a NormativeSpecification (q.v.) and AGENT is an IntelligentAgent, (normativelyBoundAgents NORM AGENT) means that AGENT is normatively constrained with respect to NORM. Normative constraints are taken here to include commitments, responsibilities, duties, and prohibitions of all sorts -- moral, legal, religious, social, familial, professional, and so on.

In some cases, the normative constraint derives primarily from some action of AGENT's that has brought NORM about. For example, AGENT might enter into an Agreement or put forth a Proposal, and thereby incur certain commitments or responsibilities. In other cases, the normative constraint derives primarily from the fact that AGENT is in the scope of some normative principle embodied in NORM. For example, by virtue of being an employed US citizen, AGENT might be subject to the general Obligation USIncomeTax. And still other cases involve constraints deriving from a combination of both of the above sources.
label: Normatively Bound Agents
normativelyBoundAgents

comment: (permissionTypeGrantsLicenseType GRANTING-TYPE LICENSE) means that GRANTING, a specialization of GrantingPermission, grants an agent an instance, INS, of a specialization of License_LegalAgreement, LICENSE. For example, (permissionTypeGrantsLicenseType (IssuingLicenseTypeFn MarriageLicense) MarriageLicense) means that (IssuingLicenseTypeFn MarriageLicense) results in the issuance of an instance of MarriageLicense.
label: Permission Type Grants License Type
permissionTypeGrantsLicenseType

comment: (logicalFieldIndexicals LS LFI) means that LFI is an indexical concept used to denote the logical value of a (logical) field in the (logical) schema, LS.

literalString

comment: (resultTypeGenlArg FUNC N) means that FUNC always returns a collection type TYPE such that (typeGenls TYPE COL), where COL is the Nth argument of FUNC. That is, the value of FUNC for any appropriate sequence of arguments is a collection of collections, each instance of which is a subcollection of the Nth item in that sequence. Symbolically, (typeGenls (FUNC ARG1..ARGN..) ARGN).
label: Result Type Genl Arg
resultTypeGenlArg

comment: (slopeRange VEHICLE ANGLE-RANGE) is the range of angles, downward to upward, at which VEHICLE is able to travel on an inclined road. Look at slopeRange.
label: on-road slope range (degrees)
slopeRange-OnRoad

comment: The predicate postalCodeOfAddress relates an instance of ContactLocation to an instance of PostalCode. (postalCodeOfAddress LOC PC) means that the location LOC has the PostalCode PC. For example, if LOC had the address: P.O. Box 1677-B, New York, NY, 10014, PC would be the string `10014'. See also ContactLocation.

postalCodeOfAddress

comment: (minorReligions GEO REL) means that Religion REL is believed in and/or practiced by a relatively small percent of the population of the GeographicalThing, GEO.

minorReligions

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function PayingWithObjectsOfTypeFn. (payingWithObjectsOfType X (PayingWithObjectsOfTypeFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.

payingWithObjectsOfType

comment: (mtDeonIdeal MT-0 MT-1) means that from the point of view of MT-0, MT-1 is considered deontically ideal --- everything ought to be the case in MT-0 is in fact the case in MT-1, and everthing is in fact the case in MT-1 is permissible to be the case in MT-0. That is to say, for each PROP, (oughtToBe PROP) holds in MT-0 only if PROP holds in MT-1, and PROP holds in MT-1 only if (permittedToBe PROP) holds in MT-0.
label: Mt Deon Ideal
mtDeonIdeal

comment: (memberTypes ORG AGENTTYPE) means that the Organization ORG typically has instances of AGENTTYPE as members or employees. Thus a particular law firm (an instance of LawFirm) has Lawyers working for it, for example (memberTypes SullivanAndCromwell Lawyer). See also orgTypeTypicallyHasMemberTypes which relates the firm type to the member type, and groupMemberType.

memberTypes

comment: rdfs:range is an imported RDFS/XML term equivalent to the Cyc term arg2Isa
label: range
rdfs:range

serverConnectionRequestInformationOf

label: Secondary Consumer In Ecosystem
secondaryConsumerInEcosystem

oeRelevantInverse

queryHasVeryHighPertinenceForType

lexicalNodeInterpretation

(recruitingOrganization RECRUITING ORG) means that ORG is the Organization on whose behalf and at whose direction the RecruitingActivity RECRUITING is carried out. This entails, among other things, that ORG is both the directingAgent and the intendedBeneficiary of RECRUITING.

recruitingOrganization

comment: A binary UnderspecifiedPredicate (q.v.). (requires_Underspecified THING REQUIREMENT) means that there is some sense in which THING requires, needs, depends on, or is conditional upon REQUIREMENT. See the many specializations of requires_Underspecified for the range of senses that this is meant to cover.

comment: A KEFacilitationPredicate and specialization of keRelevantInverse that relates a collection to a binary predicate. (keStrongSuggestionInverse COL BINPRED) means that for every known (i.e. Cyc-reified) instance INST of COL, it is strongly suggested that there be some reified THING such that (BINPRED THING INST) is known in the Knowledge Base. See also keWeakSuggestionInverse and keStrongSuggestionPreds.
label: Ke Strong Suggestion Inverse
keStrongSuggestionInverse

comment: A RelativeLocationalPredicate that relates a spatial object to the surfaces that are parts (or the whole) of the boundary between the object and that which is not the object. (objectSurfaces OBJECT SURFACE) means that SURFACE is one of the surfaces of OBJECT.

comment: (relevantInTime_Always MT TIME) means that the assertions in MT are relevant throughout the entire temporal extent of TIME. See also relevantInTime_Sometime.

label: Polity Has Transport Means
polityHasTransportMeans
Scheduled Number Of Stops
scheduledNumberOfStops
comment: (scheduledNumberOfStops TRANSPORTING NUMBER) is used to relate an instance of TransportationEvent to the number of stops NUMBER made during the journey. Stops are those subevents of any instance of TransportationEvent in which the driverActor is scheduled or intends to halt for a period of time. This predicate maybe used to relate the number of stops a person intends to make while running errands aa well as the number of scheduled stops on a train or bus trip. During the course of the actual trip, more or fewer stops may occur.

label: Slots Additive
slotsAdditive
comment: (slotsAdditive SUM-SLOT ADD-SLOT) expresses the following relationship between two QuantitySlots: the value of SUM-SLOT applied to OBJ is (by definition or convention) the sum of OBJ's value on ADD-SLOT plus zero or more other values. For example, it is true that (slotsAdditive financialAssetsOfAgent cashAssetsOfAgent), because the value of an agent's financial assets is the sum of the value of her cash assets plus other values (e.g., of her stock holdings, securities, etc.).

A spec pred of substring, (prefixSubstring PREFIX STRING) is true iff i) PREFIX is a substring of STRING and PREFIX occurs at the beginning of STRING. For example, (prefixSubstring "lazy" "lazy dog") is true whereas (prefixSubstring "zy do" "lazy dog") is false. See also suffixSubstring.
label: Prefix Substring
prefixSubstring

comment: Where FN is a RelationDenotingFunction, (resultArity FN N) means that every Relation denoting CycL term that is generated with the CycL term denoting FN in the arg 0 position denotes a Relation with arity N. For example, (resultArity OfDateFn 2) means that every CycL predicate reified via a term that uses OfDateFn as the main operator, e.g. (OfDateFn CalendarDay), has arity 2.
label: Result Arity
resultArity

comment: (releases_Underspecified CONTAINER CONTENTS) states that the abstract container CONTAINER in some underspecified (possibily metaphoric or non-spatial) manner once but no longer contains CONTENTS. For instance, we might say (releases_Underspecified Alcatraz_ThePrison SeanConnery) or more figuratively, (releases_Underspecified MicrosoftInc MSWindows).
label: Releases-Underspecified
releases-Underspecified

comment: This functional predicate relates a physical schema with the unique set of physical fields with the following properties (i) the set defines a key for the schema (see schemaKeys for a definition of a key) and (ii) this key in particular was chosen by the schema designers to be the canonical reference to individual elements of the schema. See also the sibling predicate secondaryKeys. Together, primaryKey and secondaryKeys partition schemaKeys. That is, if (schemaKeys SCHEMA KEY) is true, then either (primaryKey SCHEMA KEY) is true, or (secondaryKeys SCHEMA KEY) is true, but never both simultaneously.
label: Primary Key
primaryKey

comment: An ActorSlot and a specialization of objectHarmed. (maleficiary EVENT AGENT) means that the Agent_Generic AGENT is harmed (in some sense) by the occurrence of the Event EVENT. In some cases, this is consistent with EVENT being (in some sense) beneficial to AGENT. For example, being punished might harm one in the short run, but benefit one in the long run. Thus the fact that maleficiary is a required actor slot for Punishing does not entail that Punishing is always (completely) detrimental to the person punished.
label: maleficiary

comment: (lexicalNodeCategory NODE SPEECHTYPE) denots the lexical node category of NODE, associating with the word form SPEECHTYPE.
label: Lexical Node Category
lexicalNodeCategory

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function MtOfIndustryOfRegionFn. (mtOfIndustryOfRegion X (MtOfIndustryOfRegionFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.

This predicate is notAssertible, since it must always be recomputed from the current state of the genls hierarchy. Moreover, it is merely the elInverse of nearestGenls.
label: Nearest Specs

ontologyVersionInfo

(organizationName_Standard TERM STRING) means that the ProperNameString STRING is one of the standard names for the thing denoted by TERM. These will normally be either the official name of an organization, or a slight variation on that name. Thus, "IBM, Inc." might be a standard name for IBMInc, just as "IBM, Incorporated" might be one. A company should be related to its official name with organizationName_Official.
label: Organization Name Standard
organizationName-Standard

comment: This predicate relates a type of character-string token to certain specializations within that type. (modeOfStringType MODE TYPE) means that MODE is a specialization of TYPE whose instances all realize the corresponding character-string in the same general way, e.g. as inscriptions, or as sounds, or as electromagnetic encodings. For example, if MODE is an instance of CharacterStringMode_Sounded and TYPE corresponds to the string 'hello', then MODE is the collection of all sounded tokens of 'hello'.
label: Mode Of String Type
modeOfStringType

comment: A predicate corresponding to the function MilitaryPostingFn. (militaryPosting X (MilitaryPostingFn X)) will always be true for X meeting the relevant arg constraints.

militaryPosting

productBetaTesterForModel

onRoadSlopeRange-Percent

operationSubsumesReplacementProcedureOnAnimalBodyPartType

label: National Infrastructure Req
nationalInfrastructureReq

(objectSecureToDegree OBJECT SECURITY-LEVEL), means that OBJECT (in the current context) is secure to the degree SECURITY-LEVEL. To further specify the context (i.e., to specify what OBJECT is secure against, use objectSecureToDegreeAgainstRoleInType.

predicateImplicitlyInvokesType-ArgIsa

softwareParameterValueShortDescription

For example, "every mountain has a summit" may be expressed as (properGeographicalSubRegionTypes Mountain Summit).
label: Proper Geographical Sub Region Types
properGeographicalSubRegionTypes
Launch Range Operations Commander
launchRangeOperationsCommander
comment: (launchRangeOperationsCommander LAUNCH PERSON) means that on the day of LAUNCH, PERSON is responsible for providing command and control of range operations capability, and for passing operations-related information to the SLCC and OD. Here 'operations related' is defined as anything that affects range operations and safety capability. The launchRangeOperationsCommander also provides go/no-go status for the range to the launchOperationsDirector.

The predicate that corresponds to the function OfDateFn. (functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical PRED CALENDAR-COVERING-TYPE) means that PRED, an instance of DateExtractionPredicate is a predicate that relates a date DATE to the unique instance of CalendarCoveringType that intersects DATE. For example, (predExtractsDateOfCalendarCoveringType calendarDayOfDate CalendarDay) means that calendarDayOfDate relates a date DATE to the calendar day that intersects DATE.
label: Pred Extracts Date Of Calendar Covering Type
predExtractsDateOfCalendarCoveringType

label: Number Of Interior Rings Of Polygon
numberOfInteriorRingsOfPolygon

mutually-negating-predicate: Ke Relation Strengthens Via All Args Inverse
comment: If (keRelationStrengthensViaAllArgs RELATION BINPRED ARGNUM) and (BINPRED WEAK STRONG), then (keStrengtheningSuggestion (RELATION ... WEAK ...) (RELATION ... STRONG ...)). In other words, (keRelationStrengthensViaAllArgs RELATION BINPRED ARGNUM) means that the binary predicate BINPRED can be used to strengthen a sentence with arg0 RELATION (or used inversely to weaken it) by replacement of any argument (except arg0). It is not a requirement that all potential replacement sentences be well-formed. RELATION will typically have variable arity.
label: Ke Relation Strengthens Via All Args
keRelationStrengthensViaAllArgs

comment: (physicalFieldIndexicals SCHEMA INDEXICAL) means that INDEXICAL is an indexical used to denote the value in a row for a physical field in the physical schema, SCHEMA. This predicate is a typedGenlPreds of schemaFieldIndexicals. See also physicalFields for a similar predicate for relating a physical field to a physical schema. Assertions using this predicate are typically inferred from forward rules.
label: Physical Field Indexicals
physicalFieldIndexicals

comment: (seesThat AGENT PROP) means that AGENT perceives, by sense of sight, that PROP is true.
label: Sees That
seesThat

comment: A specialization (see genlPreds) of properPhysicalParts, (objectHasBase OBJECT BASE) identifies BASE as the base (see Base_Support) of the instance of PartiallyTangible, OBJECT.
label: base
objectHasBase

comment: How long would this product remain useful for its intended purpose if it were kept under recommended storage conditions (temperature, humidity, etc.), if it were never used, and its packaging, if any, were never opened. (shelfLife PRODUCT INTERVAL) means that from (StartFn PRODUCT) for a period equal to INTERVAL, PRODUCT is predicted to be useful for its intended purpose. Note that the actual length of time an unused product stays useful may be longer or shorter than its shelflife. Freezing some perishable products increases how long they remain useable, and exposing some products to the atmosphere, heat, humidity, etc., can cause them to go bad in a time shorter than their shelf life. This predicate is intended for products that deteriorate significantly over a period of anywhere from less than a day to at most several years, including flowers, food, and pharmaceuticals. It does NOT denote the actual amount of time spent on a shelf.
label: shelf life
shelfLife

comment: (smells AGENT OBJECT) means that AGENT perceives the physical object or event OBJECT via the sense of smell. This implies that OBJECT releases (or involves the release of) a scent (see Odor) of which AGENT is sensuously aware. In the situation described by "Joe smells the coffee brewing", both of the following are true: (smells Joe Coffee01) and (smells Joe CoffeeBrewingEvent09).
label: smelling
smells

comment: (localEMailFileForAccount FILE ACCOUNT) means that the EMailFile FILE is a repository for the electronic mail of the ComputerAccount ACCOUNT which has been "pulled down" from the mail server and stored on some user's machine. For email which is still on the server, see mailboxFileForAccount.
label: Local E Mail File For Account
localEMailFileForAccount

comment: A binary SummaryPredicate and specialization of interestingSentence that relates an NormativeSpecification to a CycLSentence_Assertible. (specificationDocumentationDataSentence N-SPEC SENTENCE) means that SENTENCE documents some fact about N-SPEC.

maximumDepth

comment:
A BinaryPredicate that relates a TextualPCW to a Language. (languageOriginallyWrittenIn WORK LANGUAGE) means that WORK was originally written (primarily) in LANGUAGE (though it may have translations in other languages). For example:

(languageOriginallyWrittenIn WarAndPeace_TheNovel RussianLanguage)
(languageOriginallyWrittenIn MobyDickNovel EnglishLanguage)
(languageOriginallyWrittenIn DonQuixote_TheBook SpanishLanguage)

To state the language that a TextuallySpecificWork (e.g. a particular EnglishLanguage translation of WarAndPeace_TheNovel) is written in, use languageWrittenIn (q.v.).
label: Language Originally Written In
languageOriginallyWrittenIn

For example, (mtAreaValue MT (SquareMile 1 1000)) means that when reasoning proceeds using the knowledge in MT, only objects having an that measures greater than or equal to 1 square mile, and less than or equal to 1000 square mile, should be considered relevant.

mtAreaValue

(processThreads PROCESS THREAD) means that THREAD is a thread of the process PROCESS.

comment: This predicate states that its arg2 (a CycLConstant) is acting as a placeholder for arg1 (which can be anything). This is similar to specs of equals but avoids any inference pitfalls that such specs might run into. The proximal motivation for this constant is to work around the problems created by the SchemaObjectFns for the BBN/CDE strengthening project, particularly the occasionally-horrendous access times to the database, and the fact that the SchemaObjectFns tend to neutralize or bog down inferences using predicates like isa and genls.

Qa Prefer Pred For Followup Generation

comment: (qaPreferPredForFollowupGeneration BETTER-PRED WORSE-PRED) means that the Predicate BETTER-PRED is preferred over the Predicate WORSE-PRED when generating qaFollowupConcepts for the QueryAugmentationApplication. It is designed to be used in stating exceptions to rules that conclude (qaFollowupConcepts FORT FORMAT-STRING FOLLOWUP). Suppose that the rules would generate two sets of bindings in which the two FORTs are identical, and the two FOLLOWUPs are identical, but FORMAT-STRING differs in the two binding sets because different predicates, having different qaConceptPrintString values, were used to generate the followups. Generally, the most specific FORMAT-STRING is preferred. We can control which redundant concept followup to discard by stating an exception involving the predicate qaPreferPredForFollowupGeneration. For example, suppose the query FORT is France. The assertion (qaPreferPredForFollowupGeneration capitalCity countryOfCity), in conjunction with an exception to the relevant rule that generates qaFollowupConcepts would result in the followup, 'Paris (France's capital)' and would prevent the redundant followup, 'Paris (city in France)'. There is no need to write GAFs using qaPreferPredForFollowupGeneration for Predicates that stand in genlPreds or genlInverse to each other.
The range of a distribution. This should be a list containing 2 numbers: the lowest value of the range and the highest.

comment: A SpatialPredicate that is a specialization of both spatiallyIncludes and spatiallyIntersects (qq.v.). (spatiallySubsumes SUPER SUB) means that the spatial extent of SUB lies within the spatial extent of SUPER. For example, a model ship in a bottle is not spatially subsumed by the bottle, but the lip of the bottle is spatially subsumed by the bottle. (The bottle spatiallyContains the ship.) Note that SUB might or might not be a part of SUPER. For example, a shadow cast on a wall is spatially subsumed by the surface of the wall, but is not a part of it. But note also that SUPER does have a part that is at least spatially coextensive (see cospatial) with SUB. Specializations of spatiallySubsumes include physicalDecompositions and geographicalSubRegions.
label: Spatially Subsumes
spatiallySubsumes

comment:
A PrimitiveTemporalPredicate (q.v.) that is a specialization of both cotemporal (q.v.) and equals. The predicate simultaneousWith is just the cotemporal relation restricted to TimePoints (q.v.), with respect to which (as with TimeIntervals generally) cotemporality is both a necessary and a sufficient condition for identity. (simultaneousWith T1 T2) means that T1 and T2 both extend over (and thus _are_) the same single point in time.

Note that individual TimePoints are seldom mentioned in axioms in the Cyc Knowledge Base. Most time-related axioms use ComplexTemporalPredicates (cf.), such as cotemporal, which can hold between TemporalThings of any sort.

comment: (off_UnderspecifiedSurface ACT LOC) states that an abstract locational relation holds between ACT and LOC, where LOC is an SurfaceRegion_Underspecified and ACT is some action requiring an ablative role. Only things which can be conceptualized as surfaces are thus allowable as the second argument to an 'off' relation. 'Off' is thus semantically more restrictive than 'from', and implies a touching of surfaces. Probably because of the strong relation to writing, the notion of a topic in English is conceived of as a SurfaceRegion_Underspecified (that is, one can write 'on a topic', the debate can move 'off a topic', etc.).
label: off

comment: (remainsForwardBecause RULE COMMENT) means that it is essential that RULE remain forward. RULE should not automatically be switched to backward as part of periodic KB housecleaning procedures. The motivation for such housecleaning is that assertions take longer and longer as the number of forward rules in the kb increases. As the knowledge base grows and applications are developed, special purpose forward rules accumulate as a result of daily KE activity. Many of these rules should not remain forward forever. Rather they may need to remain forward for a short time (e.g. days to weeks) during an application development phase. Such rules should not have a remainsForwardBecause meta-assertion and will be automatically switched backward at periodic (monthly?) intervals as a form of housecleaning. Clear exemplars of rules which should have remainsForwardBecause assertions include rules which conclude arity 2 based on (isa ?pred BinaryPredicate). More borderline positive exemplars of a remainsForwardBecause rules are 'documentation updating' rules. An example of such a rule is one which puts the SharedNote called #$DecidingWhichInstrumentPredicateToUse on every specialization of instrument_Generic. Perhaps rules like this can be periodically repropagated rather than continually forward propagated (such functionality is not curently (June 1998) available). It may be helpful to give uniform comments for different classes of remainsForwardBecause rules. For example assertions for 'documentation updating' rules might all have the COMMENT 'automatic SharedNotes updating.' on them. That way, as more fine grained control over forward inference is obtained, the uniformity of such comments will aid the semi-automatic assignment of such rules to the appropriate class of forward inference.
label: Remains Forward Because
remainsForwardBecause

A MetaPredicate for stating that every instance of a given collection is related (as the "arg3") to some things by a given predicate. (requiredArg3Pred COL PRED) means that for every instance INST of COL, there exists some sequence <X1, X2,..., Xn> such that (PRED X1 X2 INST ... Xn) holds. comment: A binary predicate relating specs of PartiallyTangible to their recommended exposure limits, as determined by the National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH). (recommendedExposureLimit SUBSTANCE LIMIT) means just that the recommended exposure limit of SUBSTANCE is LIMIT. A substance's recommended exposure limit ("REL") is the maximum average concentration of the substance to which a normal, healthy human adult, who works 40 hours per week, should be exposed in a work day lasting up to 10 hours. REL's have not been codified as legal limits under U.S. law. Compare permissibleExposureLimit, shortTermExposureLimit, ceiling_ExposureLimit, and iDLHConcentration.

comment:
(orderingContextArg PREDICATE ARG-NUM) identifies ARG-NUM as the argument-place for the context against which the other arguments related by PREDICATE are assigned an order.

For example, 

     (orderingContextArg subWorkPriorToSubWorkInWork 3)
means that in 
     (subWorkPriorToSubWorkInWork WORK-1 WORK-2 WORK-3)
WORK-1 and WORK-2 are ordered in the context of WORK-3 (in this case, WORK-1 "comes before" WORK-2 in WORK-3. Similarly, 
     (orderingContextArg startsAfterStartOfInSituationType 1)
means that in 
     (startsAfterStartOfInSituationType SIT-TYPE-1 SIT-TYPE-2 SIT-TYPE-3)
SIT-TYPE-2 and SIT-TYPE-3 are assigned an order in the context of SIT-TYPE-1 (in this case, SIT-TYPE-2 is a "stage" that starts after the start of the stage SIT-TYPE-3 in the larger script or process SIT-TYPE-1.

orderingContextArg

comment: A SymmetricBinaryPredicate that relates a Person to a Person. (roommates PERSON1 PERSON2) means that PERSON1 and PERSON2 are roommates, i.e. people who share a residence as a matter of convenience, and not as a family unit or romantic couple. Family members--for example, two siblings--can be roommates, provided that the related roommates do not consider themselves to be "a family," per se. (A borderline case would be a situation in which a woman moves in with her only child after her husband dies.) Typically, roommates share the burden of paying rent, utitilies, etc. Note that roommates is only transitive by default, since it is possible (though unlikely) that (roommates A B) and (roommates B C) but (not (roommates A C)). (Consider the case where B has two main residences, with different roommates at each one.)
label: roommate
roommates

comment: (personWithPosition REL PERSON) means that the Person filling the job position in a HasPositionRelationship REL is PERSON. See also JobPosition, personWithJobPosition and versionOfJobPosition.

comment: (postalCodeExtension LOCATION STRING) means that STRING is the extension (extra or completing bits) of the postal code for LOCATION. For addresses in the United States, STRING would correspond to the 4-digit extension part of a complete ZIP code, represented as a character string. Note that in other parts of the world, the extension part of the postal code (if it exists) may consist of letters, numbers, or other symbols as well (e.g., dashes, colons). See also postalCodeOfAddress and extraFourDigitsOfZip. The latter assumes that in the context of use (the Microtheory in which relevant assertions are entered), the extension part of ZIP codes will be represented as numbers rather than as character strings.
label: Postal Code Extension
postalCodeExtension

comment: This predicate relates an object to the distance that is is largest extent. For instance (maximumExtensionParameterOfObject OBJ DIST) means that length, height and width and diameter (where applicable) are all less than or equal to DIST and one or more of the extensions is equal to DIST. More straightforwardly, we might define this as the length of the longest line segment that passes through the object and whose end points are on the outer surface of the object. Note that this will often be the length of the object but there are some situations in which the length won't be the greatest extension. Also note that this predicate does not relate all spatial things to a distance. For instance, spatially disconnected things would not have a greatest extension.
label: Maximum Extension Parameter Of Object

comment:
A symmetric, irreflexive RelativeLocationalPredicate that is a specialization of spatiallyIntersects (q.v.) and a contrary (see negationPreds) of spatiallySubsumes (q.v.). (partiallySpatiallyIntersects OBJECT1 OBJECT2) means that the spatial extents of OBJECT1 and OBJECT2 overlap, but only partially, so that neither is completely included in the other. Thus, there is some part of OBJECT1 that is disjoint with OBJECT2, and vice versa.

For example, the sonoran desert, which straddles the US and Mexico, partially intersects both of those countries. And the circular regions in a standard Venn diagram partially intersect one another.

See also the specialization #$partiallyOverlappingSpaceRegions.
label: Partially Spatially Intersects

ORG will be an instance of PLOIDY-LEVEL just in case all its cells (with the exception of Gametes) have the number of copies of chromosome sets characterized by PLOIDY-LEVEL.

comment: If (responsibleFor AGENT SIT) holds at time t, this means that, sometime prior to time t AGENT deliberately performed an action which was instrumental in bringing about SIT to the extent that, other things being equal, if the action had not been performed, SIT would not have come about. This sense of 'responsibility' is stronger than causal responsibility--ie, it requires that AGENT play more than an unwitting causal role in bringing about SIT; however, it is probably weaker than full-blown moral responsibility, since even though AGENT intended to perform the action which brought about SIT, AGENT might not have intended to bring about SIT. This is roughly the level of responsibility that applies, eg, to a case where somebody has killed a pedestrian by recklessly running a stop sign: the malefactor may not have intended to kill the pedestrian, but a deliberate decision of the malefactor's nevertheless was instrumental in causing the pedestrian's death. It is a necessary condition for the stronger sense of responsibility aforementioned, and is probably a sufficient condition for the weaker sense of causal responsibility aforementioned.
label: responsibility
responsibleFor

comment: (rejectsProposal REJECTING PROPOSAL) means that the communication act REJECTING rejects PROPOSAL which is the information content of some propoasl.

In other words, (moreLikelyThanNot_Conditional EVIDENCE HYPOTHESIS) is shorthand for 
(moreLikelyThanGivenThat EVIDENCE HYPOTHESIS (not HYPOTHESIS)).

comment: The predicate objectActedOn is used to relate an event to any object significantly affected in that event. The entity or entities in question must exist before the event, but may be either destroyed in the event (see the more specific predicate inputsDestroyed), or merely affected by it (for example, see the more specific predicates damages and objectOfStateChange). (objectActedOn EVENT OBJECT) means that OBJECT is altered or affected in EVENT, and the change that OBJECT undergoes is central or focal to understanding EVENT. Thus, scissors are not an objectActedOn in a HairCuttingEvent. The focal change in a haircut is hair getting shorter; thus, hair is a legitimate objectActedOn in a HairCuttingEvent. The almost microscopic dulling that scissors undergo in a single haircut is a comparatively insignificant change with respect to a single haircut, considered as a HairCuttingEvent.
label: affected object
objectActedOn

comment: A PhysicalPartPredicate and specialization of physicalParts that relates an object with tangible and intangible parts (see CompositeTangibleAndIntangibleObject) to its greatest tangible part. (physicalExtent WHOLE PART) means that PART is the complete part of WHOLE that is PartiallyTangible and not itself a CompositeTangibleAndIntangibleObject (and thus does not include any intangible part of WHOLE). For example, the physicalExtent of a given copy of "Moby Dick" includes the cover, the pages, and their markings; it excludes the AspatialInformationStore and the ConceptualWork that are also in some sense present in that copy of "Moby Dick".
label: Physical Extent
physicalExtent

comment:
A binary predicate used to state the modulus or base used to compute equivalent quantity expressions for units of measure that are congruent with respect to a fixed quantity (the base). (quantityCongruenceBase BASE QUANTITYTYPE) means that if UNIT is a UnitOfMeasure which denotes quantities of type QUANTITYTYPE and VAL1 and VAL2 are both admittedArguments of UNIT, then (UNIT VAL1) is said to be congruent to (UNIT VAL2) modulo UNIT if and only if there exists some Integer N such that 
  (UNIT VAL1) = (UNIT VAL2) + N*BASE.
It is easy to see that (UNIT VAL1) is conguent modulo UNIT to (UNIT VAL1) + N*BASE for any Integer N, and so there are a countably infinite number of quantities that are congruent to (UNIT VAL1). There is exactly one, however, that is greater than or equal to (UNIT 0) and strictly less than BASE. This quantity is called the common residue of (UNIT VAL1). In Cyc, the function ResidueFn and the predicate commonResidue compute the common residue of a quantity using the asserted extent of quantityCongruenceBase.
label: Quantity Congruence Base
quantityCongruenceBase

comment: The functionCorrespondingPredicate_Canonical of SpatialScaleComparableIndividualsFn.

scalingCollectionOfWithRespectToSpatialMetrics

comment: (retainTermBecause NAT DOCUMENTED-REASON) means that for reasons specified in the english text DOCUMENTED-REASON the non-atomic term NAT will not be 'forgotten' during 'NAT forgetting KB cleanups'. Such periodically performed KB cleanups automatically remove ('forget') references to non-atomic terms (NATs) unless a given NAT has something stated about it which is not concluded from its termOfUnit. For example, a NAT which has no local assertions but does have a rule concluding something about it will be 'forgotten' when the cleanup function is run since that rule concluded via a termOfUnit literal which satisfied its antecedent. However, a NAT which has a local assertion or which has (retainTermBecause NAT DOCUMENTED-REASON) asserted about it will not be forgotten. See also ephemeralTerm.
label: Retain Term Because
retainTermBecause

comment:
A binary IntangibleObjectPredicate. (lawPrescribesActType LAW ACTTYPE) means that LAW requires any agent subject to it (see subjectToCOC) to perform at least one (and in some cases more, possibly regularly-recurring) instances of ACTTYPE. This of course does not imply that such acts are performed, since laws are sometimes violated.

For example, a law might require everyone within a certain age range to register for the miltary draft. Or a law might require a given parent to make monthly child-support payments to their child's other parent.

See also lawProscribesActType.
label: Law Prescribes Act Type
lawPrescribesActType

(orthogonalSetsOrCollections SETORCOL1 SETORCOL2) means that each of SETORCOL1 and SETORCOL2 has at least one element that the other lacks, and that at least one thing is an element of both collections. It thus entails that all of the following are true:

(2) (not (subsetOf SETORCOLL1 SETORCOLL2));
(3) (not (subsetOf SETORCOLL2 SETORCOLL1)).

comment:
A RuleMacroPredicate and a specialization of physicalPartTypes. Where TYPE1 and TYPE2 are both specializations of PartiallyTangible, (properPhysicalPartTypes TYPE1 TYPE2) means that every instance of TYPE1 has an instance of TYPE2 as a proper physical part. For example, (properPhysicalPartTypes RoseBouquet RoseFlower).

Most assertions with properPhysicalPartTypes are default true, because it is generally possible for some instances of a collection to lack parts of a type that most instances of that collection always have. For example, (properPhysicalPartTypes Finger Fingernail) is default true, even though a some fingers might lack fingernails as parts.

Cf. normalWholeTypeForPartType, which is used to relate typical part types to the whole types of which they are ordinarily parts.

comment: An instance of SpecificEntryFormatPredicate (q.v.). (singleEntryFormatInArgs PRED N) means that, for any particular way of fixing the other arguments to PRED besides the Nth, there is at most one thing such that, if taken as the Nth argument, PRED holds of those arguments. That is, if the sequences <... ARGN ...> and <... ARGN-PRIME ...> differ at most in their Nth items and both (PRED ... ARGN ...) and (PRED ... ARGN-PRIME ...) hold, then ARGN = ARGN-PRIME (see equals). For example, singleEntryFormatInArgs holds of biologicalMother with respect to its second argument-place, since an animal can only have one biological mother. A predicate with a single-entry format argument-place is thus a StrictlyFunctionalPredicate (q.v.) that is "functional" with respect to that argument-place (see strictlyFunctionalInArgs). Contrast with openEntryFormatInArgs.
label: Single Entry Format In Args

comment:
A binary predicate that represents logical entailment in CycL. (sentenceImplies ANTECEDENT CONSEQUENT) means that CONSEQUENT can be derived from ANTECEDENT using purely logical transformations. For example, this holds by double negation: 
  (sentenceImplies
    (isa Muffet Poodle)
    (not (not (isa Muffet Poodle))) .
Note that there are cases in which (implies ANTECEDENT CONSEQUENT) is analytically true, or necessarily true in some sense of necessity weaker than logical necessity, such that (sentenceImplies ANTECEDENT CONSEQUENT) is false. For example, whereas: 
  (implies (isa Muffet Poodle) (isa Muffet Dog))
is analytically true or in some sense necessarily true, 
  (sentenceImplies (isa Muffet Poodle) (isa Muffet Dog))
is not true, since the material conditional is not logically valid.

sentenceImplies also differs from implies in that whereas implies is a LogicalConnective (q.v.), sentenceImplies is merely a predicate that holds between sentences. sentenceImplies is primarily intended to be used for rules that quantify over CycL sentences.
label: Sentence Implies
sentenceImplies

comment:
A binary MetaRelation predicate that holds between functions and expression-types. resultQuotedIsa indicates that any value returned by a given Function_Denotational is a "quoted instance" of a given expression-type. More correctly, (resultQuotedIsa FUNC TYPE) means that, for any term-sequence ARGS, if the expression (FUNC . ARGS) is an admittedNAT (q.v.), then it is an instance of the SubLExpressionType TYPE. That is, the following holds: 
  (quotedIsa (FUNC . ARGS) TYPE)
And, equivalently, so does: 
  (isa (Quote (FUNC . ARGS)) TYPE)
To contrast this predicate with resultIsa: (resultIsa FUNC COL) holds just in case each defined term of the form (FUNC . ARGS) denotes an instance of COL, whereas (resultQuotedIsa FUNC COL) holds just in case each admitted (i.e. syntactically and semantically well-formed) term of the form (FUNC . ARGS) is itself an instance of COL.
label: Result Quoted Isa
resultQuotedIsa

A binary predicate that relates a given MapProjection (q.v.) to the Point from which points in the projectionSource are projected to either the projectionIntermediate (if there is one) or the projectionTarget. (projectionPointOfOrigin PROJ ORIGIN) means that in PROJ some or all points on the source surface SOURCE are projected from ORIG. That is, there is some point SOURCEPOINT in SOURCE is projected to the point TARGETPOINT in the intermediate or target surface (as the case may be) at which that surface intersects the line passing through ORIG and SOURCEPOINT. If PROJ is a PerspectiveProjection (q.v.), then every point in SOURCE is projected in that same way with respect toORIG.
