A MetaRelation predicate that associates a given Relation with its set-theoretic range: the set of all and only things to which the relation relates something. For example, the range of likesAsFriend is the set of sentient animals who are liked by some sentient animal or other, and the range of DifferenceFn is the set of all instances of ScalarInterval (since each scalar interval is the result of subtracting some scalar interval from some scalar interval). (relationRange RELATION RANGE) means that the range of RELATION is RANGE. More precisely (and following standard mathematical practice): if the relationalArity (q.v.) of RELATION is N (for N > 1), RANGE is the set of all the Nth-members of the N-length instances of List that are in the relationExtension (q.v.) of RELATION; if RELATION is unary it has no range, and relationRange is undefined for such a RELATION. (Note that if FUNCTION is a VariableArityFunction (q.v.) there will be no particular length N shared by each of the lists in its extension.) Though defined for polyadic relations generally, RANGE will normally be of particular interest only when RELATION is a function (see Function_Denotational), in which case RELATION relates each element of its relationDomain (q.v.) DOMAIN to exactly one element of RANGE, and each element of RANGE is related by RELATION to at least one element of DOMAIN. See also RangeOfFunctionFn and inRangeOf.
label: Relation Range
relationRange

An AsymmetricBinaryPredicate and a specialization of subSituations. This predicate relates situations to further situations which are their proper parts.

(properSubSituations SIT SUBSIT) means that:
(1) the Situation SUBSIT is a part of the Situation SIT such that a complete description of SIT would have to involve a description of SUBSIT, and
(2)SUBSIT is not identical to SIT itself.

For example, a situation in which a car engine is non-functioning might have as a proper subsituation the situation of a carburetor being misconfigured.
label: Proper Sub Situations
properSubSituations

comment: (sourceNodeInSystem X SYS) means that X is a source node in the Semi_DirectedPathSystem SYS, i.e., a node that all links attached to it go 'out' from it and no such links come 'in' to it. A source node X in SYS is a node in SYS such that X is on some links but no loops in SYS, and such that each link in SYS that X is on is a link directed from X to another node (but not from another to X). Another way to put this is that X is a node in SYS that is neither on a loop in SYS, nor an isolated node in SYS, nor a node to which a link in SYS is directed. Note that if a node X in SYS is on a 'bidirected' link, i.e., a link directed both from X to Y and from Y to X for some node Y, then X cannot be a source node in SYS. See loopInSystem, isolatedNodeInSystem and linkFromToInSystem.
label: Source Node In System
sourceNodeInSystem

For example,

For stating precise opposite direction see the specialization oppositeDirection_Precise.

Query Variable
queryVariable
comment:
(queryVariable QUERY-SPEC SET) means that in response to the query specification QUERY-SPEC (which is a query with exactly one free variable), the CycInferenceEngine currently generates an assignment SET of bindings.

For example, the following is currently true: 

 (queryVariable
   (QueryFn  
     (ist SimpleAstronomyDataVocabularyMt
     (isa ?PLANET Planet))
   (TheSet
       PlanetMars    PlanetEarth   PlanetTauBooB  PlanetMercury     
       PlanetVenus   PlanetSaturn  PlanetNeptune  PlanetJupiter
       PlanetUranus  PlanetPluto))

See also queryAnswers and queryBindings.

(orgTypesSimilarWithRespectToGenotype ORGTYPE1 ORGTYPE2) means that instances of ORGTYPE1 have Genomes that are similar, possibly suggesting a common evolutionary origin. A binary MetaRelation that relates a ScopingRelation (q.v.) to an integer indicating the argument-place of the former that takes a variable or list of variables. (scopingArg RELN N) means that RELN's Nth argument is a variable or variable-list (see CycLVariable and CycLVariableList) such that it (they) and any other occurrences of the same variable(s) that occur free in the CycL formula serving as the "scoped" argument (see scopedFormulaArg) to RELN is (are) bound with respect to the entire RELN-based formula. For example, (scopingArg thereExists 1) entails that in the sentence 

  (thereExists ?KIT

(redundantAssertions ASSN-1 ASSN-2) means that ASSN-1 and ASSN-2 entail each other. Note that this is not currently a replacement for the [R] notation one sees automatically generated on redundant genls or isa assertions. Rather, its primary purpose is to label pairs of assertions whose mutual entailment is hard for the system to automatically deduce. It is much more likely that human Cyclists will notice the redundancies. Although not currently (March 97) supported, redundantAssertions may help the system narrow search. E.g. if ASSN-1 has already been used in an inference path, attempt to use ASSN-2 with the same priority that one would wish to re-use ASSN-1. It also may be useful in helping us induce preferential synactic forms. For example imagine two syntactic classes of assertions A and B. Suppose there are a large number of assertions a in A and b in B such that (redundantAssertions a b) is true. Further, suppose that assertions in A are used in inference paths 10 times more often than those in B in a suite of several thousand application related inferences. This would indicate that knowledge enterers should prefer syntactic forms similar to those in A over syntactic forms to those in B. For an assertion that is a special case of a more general assertion see assertionIsArgumentFor.
label: Redundant Assertions
redundantAssertions

comment:
This predicate relates IntentionalMentalSituations (q.v.) to their "intentional objects": the things they are "of" or "about". (objectOfMentalSituation SIT THING) means that SIT is of, about, or directed toward THING. SIT might be an occurrent intentional mental act, such as a perceptual act of seeing the Eiffel Tower, or a more long-term intentional mental state, such as a propositional attitude of believing that the Eiffel Tower is located in Paris. In both examples, an object of SIT would be the Tower; the second example also has the city of Paris (and arguably the located-in relation as well) as an object.

Note that, although they are indirectly related (see e.g. PurposefulMentalActivity), the sense of "intentional" described above is not to be confused with its other sense as an antonym of "accidental".

See also subjectOfMentalSituation and thinksAbout.
label: Object Of Mental Situation
objectOfMentalSituation

comment: (reformulatorRule EXPR-1 EXPR-2), asserted in the microtheory MT, means that EXPR-1 may be reformulated into EXPR-2 (or vice versa, based on meta-properties of this rule and what mode the reformulator is in) in MT or a specMt thereof. Free variables in EXPR-1 and EXPR-2 are shared, and may bind with CycL expressions which match the template. Truth and semantics are not necessarily preserved (see TruthPreservingReformulation). Use the more specific predicates reformulatorEquiv and reformulatorEquals when applicable.
label: Reformulator Rule
reformulatorRule

This predicate relates an agent to a type of event s/he needs to do in order to achieve or further some (unspecified) goal (as in "Pam needs to buy some groceries"). The intended sense of `needs' includes, but is not limited to, matters of life and death; see the comment on needs_Generic for a fuller account. (needsToDo AGENT EVENTTYPE) means that AGENT needs to fill the doneBy actor slot (or some specialization thereof) with respect to an (indeterminate, future) instance of EVENTTYPE. Calling the instance "indeterminate" reflects an assumption that there is no one particular instance of EVENTTYPE such that AGENT needs to do _it_. (To assume otherwise would be highly dubious. For it is far from obvious that there is any meaningful sense in which future events exist in the present; and even if they do, should AGENT's need go unfulfilled there might not even be any _future_ instance of EVENTTYPE that could be the one that she needed to do.) Rather, AGENT's need could be satisfied by her being the "doer" in _any_ future instance of EVENTTYPE, modulo whatever practical constraints are imposed on AGENT by her circumstances. (E.g. Pam must buy those groceries within the next few days or it will be too late.) What AGENT needs to do an EVENTTYPE for (i.e. what goal of hers it would further) and what will happen to AGENT if she fails to do so (e.g. whether she will die, suffer an important loss, or just be noticeably inconvenienced) are left unspecified in the above formula, though in practice they might be inferable from other assertions in the context (see e.g. needsFor). Note that, as with the other specializations of needs_Generic, needsToDo has to do with a more-or-less "objective" requirement of AGENT's to do an EVENTTYPE, and does not entail a corresponding "felt need" on the part of AGENT. (E.g. Pam herself might not realize that her cupboards are bare.) A felt need of this sort is perhaps best represented as an assertion that a given agent both knows that s/he objectively needsToDo a certain type of event and desires that s/he do so. See also the other specializations of needs_Generic.
label: Needs To Do
needsToDo

comment:
A specialization of both recipientOfInfo and communicationTarget that is used to indicate who among those who receive information in a communication event were also intended to receive the information. (recipientOfInfo_Intended COMM RECIPIENT) holds whenever (i) RECIPIENT successfully receives the information communicated in the communication event COMM (see recipientOfInfo) and (ii) RECIPIENT is one of the Agent_Generics that the senderOfInfo in the CommunicationAct_Single COMM intended to receive the information (see communicationTarget).

For example, suppose I am speaking at a closed meeting to one or more persons on classified information and, unbeknownst to me, a spy outside the room is listening in and hears everything I am saying. If each of the persons in the meeting hears everything I am saying, then each bears the relation recipientOfInfo_Intended to each instance of CommunicationAct_Single COMM during the meeting of which I am the senderOfInfo. The spy, however, bears only the relation recipientOfInfo to each of these instances. Suppose, however, that one person at the meeting is hard of hearing and does not hear what I am saying. Each event COMM is still a CommunicationAct_Single since it had at least one subEvents that is an instance of AccessingAnIBT (at least the spy heard what was said) but the person who is hard of hearing is a communicationTarget of COMM but not a recipientOfInfo_Intended since he or she did not receive the information, i.e. was not a recipientOfInfo.

See also intendedAudience.
label: Recipient Of Info Intended
recipientOfInfo-Intended

comment: An intransitive specialization of dominantNode, and the smallest relation generalizing both optionNodes and syntacticDaughters (q.v.). (parentalNode SUB SUPER) means that node SUB is immediately "below" node SUPER in the (possibly underspecified) parse tree to which both nodes belong.

comment: A MetaFunction predicate that holds of certain CollectionRelatingFunctions with respect to certain argument-places. (resultGenlArg FUNC N) means that FUNC always returns a subcollection of its own corresponding Nth-place argument, and that FUNC is "genls preserving" in that argument-place. More precisely: (i) the value of FUNC for any sequence of arguments for which it is defined is a subcollection of the Nth item in that sequence (i.e. (genls (FUNC ARG1..ARGN..) ARGN)) and (ii) (preservesGenlsInArg FUNC N) holds. For example, (resultGenlArg JuvenileFn 1) entails (genls (JuvenileFn Dog) Dog) and -- given that (genls Dog Mammal) -- (genls (JuvenileFn Dog) (JuvenileFn Mammal)). See also resultIsaArg and resultGenl.
label: Result Genl Arg
resultGenlArg

comment: (possibleActionTypeForActiveArea_CW ACT_TYPE ACTIVE_AREA_CW) means that instantiations of ACTIVE_AREA_CW may intiate actions which are instances of ACT_TYPE, when the active area is activated. This predicate is useful when there are several different action types that could be taken, e.g. with a computer menu [ComputerDisplayMenu_CW]. If such actions are always initiated upon activation of an instance of ACTIVE_AREA_CW, use the more specific predicate: actionTypeForActiveArea_CW.
label: Possible Action Type For Active Area CW
possibleActionTypeForActiveArea-CW
